{"title_page": "Ghaziabad Junction railway station", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox station\n| name            = Ghaziabad Junction\n| native_name     = \u0917\u093e\u091c\u093c\u093f\u092f\u093e\u092c\u093e\u0926 \u091c\u0902\u0915\u094d\u0936\u0928\n| native_name_lang = hi\n| style           = Indian Railways\n| image         = [[File:Indian_Railways_Suburban_Railway_Logo.svg|100px]]\n| image_caption = Indian Railways Logo\n| address         = Station Road, Guru Govind Singh Marg, [[Ghaziabad district, India|Ghaziabad]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| country         = India\n| coordinates     = {{Coord|28.6505|N|77.4318|E|type:railwaystation_region:IN|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation       = {{convert|217.00|m|ft}}\n| line            = [[Kanpur-Delhi section]]<br/>[[Delhi-Meerut-Saharanpur line]]<br/>[[Delhi-Moradabad line]]\n| other           = \n| structure       = Standard on ground\n| platform        = 6\n| tracks          = 18\n| parking         = Yes\n| bicycle         = Yes\n| opened          = 1865-66\n| closed          = \n| rebuilt         = \n| electrified     = 1971-72\n| ADA             = \n| code            = {{Indian railway code\n  | code = GZB\n  | division = [[Delhi railway division|Delhi]]\n  }}\n| owned           = [[Indian Railways]]\n| operator        = [[Northern Railway zone|Northern Railway]]\n| status          = Functioning\n| former          = [[East Indian Railway Company]]\n| passengers      = 5,00,000\n| pass_year       = 46,00,000\n| pass_percent    = \n| pass_system     = \n| map_locator     = {{Location map|India Uttar Pradesh|lat=28.6505|long=77.4318|width=300|caption= Location in Uttar Pradesh|label='''Ghaziabad''' railway station}}\n| services = {{s-rail|title=Indian Railways}}\n{{s-line|system=Indian Railways |previous=Maripat|next=Sahibabad| line=Northern Railway zone| branch=[[Kanpur-Delhi section]]}}\n{{s-line|system=Indian Railways |previous=| next=Mehrauli| line=Northern Railway zone| branch=[[Delhi-Moradabad line]]}}\n{{s-line|system=Indian Railways |previous=| next=New Ghaziabad| line=Northern Railway zone| branch=[[Delhi-Meerut-Saharanpur line]]}}\n}}\n'''Ghaziabad railway station''' (station code:- '''GZB''') is on the [[Kanpur-Delhi section]] of [[Howrah-Delhi main line]], Howrah-Gaya-Delhi line And New Delhi-Moradabad-Lucknow line.  It is located in [[Ghaziabad district, India|Ghaziabad district]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]]. It serves [[Ghaziabad, Uttar Pradesh|Ghaziabad]].\n\n==History==\n{{main|Northern_Railway_zone#History | label 1 = Northern Railway zone history}}\n\nThrough trains started running on the [[East Indian Railway Company]]\u2019s Howrah-Delhi line in 1866.<ref name=irfcai>{{cite web| url=http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-hist.html |title=IR History: Early History (1832-1869)| publisher=IRFCA| accessdate=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe railway line between Meerut and Delhi was constructed in 1864.<ref name=triposo>{{cite web|url= http://www.triposo.com/loc/Meerut |title=Meerut |publisher= Triposo |accessdate=7 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Sind, Punjab and Delhi railway completed the {{convert|483|km|mi|0|adj=mid|-long}} Amritsar\u2013Ambala\u2013Saharanpur\u2013Ghaziabad line in 1870 connecting [[Multan Cantonment railway station|Multan]] (now in [[Pakistan]]) with Delhi.<ref>{{cite web|title=IR History: Early Days II (1870-1899) |url= http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-history2.html| accessdate=7 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Ghaziabad-Moradabad link was established by [[Oudh and Rohilkhand Railway]] in 1900.<ref name=orr>{{cite web| url=http://management.ebooks6.com/The-Oudh-Rohilkhand-Railway-download-w23852.pdf| title=The Oudh and Rohilkhand Railway| publisher=Management E-books6| accessdate=28 June 2013}}{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Electrification===\n\nThe Tundla-Aligarh-Ghaziabad sector was electrified in 1975-76, and the Ghaziabad-Nizamuddin-New Delhi-Delhi sector in 1976-77,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://irfca.org/docs/electrification-history.html| title=History of Electrification| publisher=IRFCA| accessdate=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe {{convert|140|km|mi|0|adj=mid|long}} Ghaziabad-Moradabad line was completely electrified in January 2016. The Ghaziabad-Meerut-Muzaffarnagar-Saharanpur-Roorkee-Haridwar line is also open to electric trains with effect from March 2016.\n\n==Local electric trains==\nLocal electric trains are available regularly from Ghaziabad for stations in the [[National Capital Region (India)|National Capital Region]]. Distance: [[New Delhi railway station|New Delhi]] (26&nbsp;km), [[Old Delhi railway station|Old Delhi]] (20&nbsp;km), [[Hazrat Nizamuddin railway station|Hazrat Nizamuddin]] (23&nbsp;km), [[Anand Vihar Terminal railway station|Anand Vihar Terminal]] (13&nbsp;km).<ref name=makemytrip>{{cite web |url= http://www.makemytrip.com/railways/newdelhi.html |title= Ghaziabad| publisher= Make my trip| accessdate = 28 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==List of local trains==\nLocal trains which run on a reguler interwell are EMUs, MEMUs, Passengers. Local trains start in the early morning and run till midnight.\n\n==Amenities==\nAmenities for passengers at Ghaziabad include: waiting rooms, escalators, water coolers,Water ATM, pure vegetarian restaurants, refreshment rooms, book stall, computerized reservation office, and telephone booths.<ref name=makemytrip />\n\n==Electric Loco Shed==\nThe Ghaziabad electric locomotive shed serves the Delhi area. It houses and maintains India's fastest locomotives which are mostly used in the [[Rajdhani Express|Rajdhani]], the [[Shatabdi Express|Shatabdi]] and the [[Duronto Express|Duronto]] Expresses. It stores 3 phaser locomotives like [[WAP 5]] & [[WAP 7]] locomotives.\n\nIt is currently holds 100+ [[WAP 5]] locomotives and 140+ [[WAP 7]] locomotives.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nGhaziabad railway stationboard.jpg|Ghaziabad Railway Station Board\nFile:Ghaziabad Junction roof.jpg|Ghaziabad Junction roof\nFile:An Old steam loco outside Ghaziabad Junction.jpg|An Old steam loco outside Ghaziabad Junction\nFile:Ghaziabad Junction.JPG|Ghaziabad Junction\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commonscat-inline|Ghaziabad Junction railway station}}\n*[http://indiarailinfo.com/arrivals/ghaziabad-junction-gzb/348 Trains at Ghaziabad] ''India Rail Info''\n\n{{Delhi\u2013Meerut\u2013Saharanpur line}}\n{{Top 100 booking stations of Indian Railways}}\n{{Railway stations in Uttar Pradesh}}\n\n[[Category:Railway junction stations in India]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Ghaziabad district, India]]\n[[Category:Delhi railway division]]\n[[Category:Transport in Ghaziabad, Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1865]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox station\n| name            = Ghaziabad Junction\n| native_name     = \n| native_name_lang = hi\n| style           = Indian Railways\n| image         = [[File:Indian_Railways_Suburban_Railway_Logo.svg|100px]]\n| image_caption = Indian Railways Logo\n| address         = Station Road, Guru Govind Singh Marg, [[Ghaziabad district, India|Ghaziabad]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| country         = India\n| coordinates     = {{Coord|28.6505|N|77.4318|E|type:railwaystation_region:IN|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation       = {{convert|217.00|m|ft}}\n| line            = [[Kanpur-Delhi section]]<br/>[[Delhi-Meerut-Saharanpur line]]<br/>[[Delhi-Moradabad line]]\n| other           = \n| structure       = Standard on ground\n| platform        = 6\n| tracks          = 18\n| parking         = Yes\n| bicycle         = Yes\n| opened          = 1865-66\n| closed          = \n| rebuilt         = \n| electrified     = 1971-72\n| ADA             = \n| code            = {{Indian railway code\n  | code = GZB\n  | division = [[Delhi railway division|Delhi]]\n  }}\n| owned           = [[Indian Railways]]\n| operator        = [[Northern Railway zone|Northern Railway]]\n| status          = Functioning\n| former          = [[East Indian Railway Company]]\n| passengers      = 5,00,000\n| pass_year       = 46,00,000\n| pass_percent    = \n| pass_system     = \n| map_locator     = {{Location map|India Uttar Pradesh|lat=28.6505|long=77.4318|width=300|caption= Location in Uttar Pradesh|label='''Ghaziabad''' railway station}}\n| services = {{s-rail|title=Indian Railways}}\n{{s-line|system=Indian Railways |previous=Maripat|next=Sahibabad| line=Northern Railway zone| branch=[[Kanpur-Delhi section]]}}\n{{s-line|system=Indian Railways |previous=| next=Mehrauli| line=Northern Railway zone| branch=[[Delhi-Moradabad line]]}}\n{{s-line|system=Indian Railways |previous=| next=New Ghaziabad| line=Northern Railway zone| branch=[[Delhi-Meerut-Saharanpur line]]}}\n}}\n'''Ghaziabad railway station''' is on the [[Kanpur-Delhi section]] of [[Howrah-Delhi main line]], Howrah-Gaya-Delhi line And New Delhi-Moradabad-Lucknow line.  It is located in [[Ghaziabad district, India|Ghaziabad district]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]]. It serves [[Ghaziabad, Uttar Pradesh|Ghaziabad]].\n\n==History==\n{{main|Northern_Railway_zone#History | label 1 = Northern Railway zone history}}\n\nThrough trains started running on the [[East Indian Railway Company]]\u2019s Howrah-Delhi line in 1866.<ref name=irfcai>{{cite web| url=http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-hist.html |title=IR History: Early History (1832-1869)| publisher=IRFCA| accessdate=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe railway line between Meerut and Delhi was constructed in 1864.<ref name=triposo>{{cite web|url= http://www.triposo.com/loc/Meerut |title=Meerut |publisher= Triposo |accessdate=7 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Sind, Punjab and Delhi railway completed the {{convert|483|km|mi|0|adj=mid|-long}} Amritsar\u2013Ambala\u2013Saharanpur\u2013Ghaziabad line in 1870 connecting [[Multan Cantonment railway station|Multan]] (now in [[Pakistan]]) with Delhi.<ref>{{cite web|title=IR History: Early Days II (1870-1899) |url= http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-history2.html| accessdate=7 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Ghaziabad-Moradabad link was established by [[Oudh and Rohilkhand Railway]] in 1900.<ref name=orr>{{cite web| url=http://management.ebooks6.com/The-Oudh-Rohilkhand-Railway-download-w23852.pdf| title=The Oudh and Rohilkhand Railway| publisher=Management E-books6| accessdate=28 June 2013}}{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Electrification===\n\nThe Tundla-Aligarh-Ghaziabad sector was electrified in 1975-76, and the Ghaziabad-Nizamuddin-New Delhi-Delhi sector in 1976-77,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://irfca.org/docs/electrification-history.html| title=History of Electrification| publisher=IRFCA| accessdate=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe {{convert|140|km|mi|0|adj=mid|long}} Ghaziabad-Moradabad line was completely electrified in January 2016. The Ghaziabad-Meerut-Muzaffarnagar-Saharanpur-Roorkee-Haridwar line is also open to electric trains with effect from March 2016.\n\n==Local electric trains==\nLocal electric trains are available regularly from Ghaziabad for stations in the [[National Capital Region (India)|National Capital Region]]. Distance: [[New Delhi railway station|New Delhi]] (26&nbsp;km), [[Old Delhi railway station|Old Delhi]] (20&nbsp;km), [[Hazrat Nizamuddin railway station|Hazrat Nizamuddin]] (23&nbsp;km), [[Anand Vihar Terminal railway station|Anand Vihar Terminal]] (13&nbsp;km).<ref name=makemytrip>{{cite web |url= http://www.makemytrip.com/railways/newdelhi.html |title= Ghaziabad| publisher= Make my trip| accessdate = 28 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==List of local trains==\nLocal trains which run on a reguler interwell are EMUs, MEMUs, Passengers. Local trains start in the early morning and run till midnight.\n\n==Amenities==\nAmenities for passengers at Ghaziabad include: waiting rooms, escalators, water coolers,Water ATM, pure vegetarian restaurants, refreshment rooms, book stall, computerized reservation office, and telephone booths.<ref name=makemytrip />\n\n==Electric Loco Shed==\nThe Ghaziabad electric locomotive shed serves the Delhi area. It houses and maintains India's fastest locomotives which are mostly used in the [[Rajdhani Express|Rajdhani]], the [[Shatabdi Express|Shatabdi]] and the [[Duronto Express|Duronto]] Expresses. It stores 3 phaser locomotives like [[WAP 5]] & [[WAP 7]] locomotives.\n\nIt is currently holds 100+ [[WAP 5]] locomotives and 140+ [[WAP 7]] locomotives.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nGhaziabad railway stationboard.jpg|Ghaziabad Railway Station Board\nFile:Ghaziabad Junction roof.jpg|Ghaziabad Junction roof\nFile:An Old steam loco outside Ghaziabad Junction.jpg|An Old steam loco outside Ghaziabad Junction\nFile:Ghaziabad Junction.JPG|Ghaziabad Junction\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commonscat-inline|Ghaziabad Junction railway station}}\n*[http://indiarailinfo.com/arrivals/ghaziabad-junction-gzb/348 Trains at Ghaziabad] ''India Rail Info''\n\n{{Delhi\u2013Meerut\u2013Saharanpur line}}\n{{Top 100 booking stations of Indian Railways}}\n{{Railway stations in Uttar Pradesh}}\n\n[[Category:Railway junction stations in India]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Ghaziabad district, India]]\n[[Category:Delhi railway division]]\n[[Category:Transport in Ghaziabad, Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1865]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4041:2e97:df23::2109:e501", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ghaziabad_Junction_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "Lady Miss Kier", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Lead too short|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| image           = Lady Miss Kier by Bobby Miller.jpg\n| name            = Lady Miss Kier\n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| background      = solo_singer\n| birth_name      = Kierin Magenta Kirby\n| alias           = Lady Kier, Kier Kirby\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1963|8|15}}\n| birth_place     = [[Youngstown, Ohio]], U.S.\n| origin          = New York City\n| instrument      = Vocals\n| genre           = {{flatlist|\n*[[Electronica]]\n*[[dance-pop]]\n*[[House music|house]]\n*[[Hip hop music|hip hop]]}}\n| occupation      = Singer, songwriter, DJ, [[record producer|producer]]\n| years_active    = 1986\u2013present\n| label           = [[Elektra Records|Elektra]]<br />Pluto Moon\n| associated_acts = [[Deee-Lite]]\n| website         = {{URL|ladykier.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Kierin Magenta Kirby''' (born August 15, 1963), better known as '''Lady Miss Kier''', is an American singer, songwriter, DJ, designer, fashion icon, and activist. She was the vocalist for the band [[Deee-Lite]], followed by a career as a DJ and solo songwriter. She is also known widely for her social, environmental, and human-rights activism.\n\n==Music career==\n===Deee-Lite===\nIn 1986, Kirby met Ukrainian-born Dmitry Brill (\"Supa DJ Dmitry\") in New York, when she made him silver platform boots and a glitter blue spacesuit for his band, Shazork. That same year, she began experimenting with singing and writing music with Brill.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldies.com/artist-biography/Deee-Lite.html|title=Deee-Lite Biography: OLDIES.com|publisher=Oldies.com |accessdate=April 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nShortly after their first show in 1986, Brill was introduced to [[Towa Tei]], a Japan-raised Korean DJ who Kirby and Brill invited to join the band several years later. Combining Kirby's vocal and writing talents with Brill's sampling skills and Tei's techno mixing, the three formed the band [[Deee-Lite]]. They had performances every month, with Kier designing new costumes for each one. When the band signed a seven-album deal with [[Elektra Records]] she stopped go-go dancing, which she previously had continued to do at Bentleys and The Copa.\n\nDeee-Lite's sound was a mix of [[house music|house]], [[techno]] and [[Electronic dance music|dance]] elements. Deee-Lite shot to stardom in 1990 with the release of their first album ''[[World Clique]]'' and the hit \"[[Groove Is in the Heart]]\". In [[1991 MTV Video Music Awards|1991]], MTV nominated Deee-Lite for several Video Music Awards, including Video of the Year, Best Dance Video, Best New Artist, Best Breakthrough Video, and Best Editing in a Video.\n\nKirby was very involved in the band's output: writing, producing, and performing the bulk of the band's songs. Known as much for their outrageous personae and costumes as for their music, the three took on larger-than-life alter-egos: Super DJ Dmitri, Jungle DJ Towa Towa, and Lady Miss Kier. Kirby is credited with designing and creating the look of the band, as well as much of the artwork accompanying the band's albums and marketing material. Her initial look relied on revamped and exaggerated retro '60s fashions. Her signature look was a zip-up catsuit, platform shoes and flipped hair-do.\n\nDeee-Lite followed their successful first album with ''[[Infinity Within]]'', a politically charged second album, in 1992. Their third album ''[[Dewdrops in the Garden]]'' was released in 1994 and saw a return to house roots with a new, more naturalistic tone.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} Neither of the two follow-up albums matched the commercial success of their debut. The second and third albums were hampered by difficulties with the label, which refused to promote, support touring, or fund contractual videos.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} The band functionally broke up during the writing of their third album in 1993, but Kirby and Brill decided to finish the project and tour together to promote the album before going their separate ways. In 1996, a remix album was released, and a greatest hits album was released in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/gig-reviews/lady-miss-kier/2006/02/13/1139679507664.html |title=Lady Miss Kier \u2013 Gig Reviews \u2013 Music \u2013 Entertainment|work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=February 13, 2006 |accessdate=November 13, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===International DJ and songwriting solo career===\n[[File:Lady Miss Kier Lounging.jpg|alt=|thumb|Lady Miss Kier Lounging]]\nBrill and Kirby's relationship fractured, and Deee-lite disbanded in 1995.<ref name=\"Smh.com.au\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/gig-reviews/lady-miss-kier/2006/02/13/1139679507664.html?page=2 |title=Lady Miss Kier \u2013 Gig Reviews \u2013 Music \u2013 Entertainment|work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=February 13, 2006 |accessdate=November 13, 2008}}</ref> \"When Dmitry and I split up, that was the end of the band,\" Kirby said. \"It was sad because I loved the band. I didn't want to leave the band and the music and I missed my writing partner, but we couldn't get along.\"<ref name=\"Smh.com.au\"/>\n\nIn 1995, after quitting the band, Lady Miss Kier moved to London where she began touring as a deejay and learning the technical end of production, recording, and engineering. In the late 1990s, she collaborated on the albums of [[Bootsy Collins]], I Kamanchi and [[A Guy Called Gerald]]. In 2002, she contributed an exclusive solo track called \"I'm Not Staying at Home\" to the compilation ''Straight Up & Dirty''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/4444-Lady-Kier |title=Lady Kier Discography |publisher=discogs |date=August 15, 1963 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> Since going solo, she has featured and co-written with artists such as Full Cycle, [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]], Junie Morrison, A Guy Called Gerald, Apollo Heights, and several P-Funk luminaries. Outside of the studio, she continued to showcase her live performances with new material for various music, film, and art festivals, as well as headlining numerous Gay Pride events worldwide. In 2012 she began performing a Deee-Lite tribute for various occasions, including the 2013 Paris Fashion Week for [[Kenzo]]<ref name=\"vmagazine.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vmagazine.com/site/content/758/party-with-kenzo |title=V Magazine / Party With Kenzo |publisher=Vmagazine.com |accessdate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816090846/http://www.vmagazine.com/site/content/758/party-with-kenzo |archivedate=August 16, 2015 }}</ref> as well as a tribute to legendary NYC DJ [[Mark Kamins]] at Santos Party House.<ref>{{cite web|last=Augustin |first=Camille |url=http://www.vibe.com/photo-gallery/everybody-celebrates-mark-kamins-santos-party-house-tribute-tonight |title=\"Everybody\" Celebrates Mark Kamins at Santos Tribute Tonight |work=Vibe |date=April 17, 2013 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs a DJ, she has spun internationally for over 17 years at thousands of clubs and major festivals including [[Coachella Festival]] (2007),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coachellarecordings.com/sources.cfm?bandid=561&year=2007 |title=Lady Miss Kier \u2013 Coachella 2007 |publisher=Coachella Recordings |date=April 28, 2007 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> Berlin's Berghain (2010)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://berghain.de/event/162 |title=Berghain Berlin &#124; Programm: 31 December 2010 |publisher=Berghain.de |date=December 31, 2010 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> and Sydney Mardi Gras (2012),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samesame.com.au/news/7619/Heres-Mardi-Gras-2012 |title=Here's Mardi Gras 2012! |publisher=Samesame.com.au |accessdate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924094037/http://www.samesame.com.au/news/7619/Heres-Mardi-Gras-2012 |archivedate=September 24, 2015 }}</ref> as well as radio programs such as East Village Radio<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eastvillageradio.com/content/content.php?id=6192 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 10, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110183059/http://www.eastvillageradio.com/content/content.php?id=6192 |archivedate=January 10, 2014 }}</ref> and Sirius XM.<ref>{{cite web |last=Belverio |first=Glenn |url=http://dianepernet.typepad.com/diane/2013/06/sarko-taylor-bar-with-anita-sarko-scott-taylor-on-siriusxm-channel-28-the-spectrum-saturdays-11pm-ps.html |title=Diane, A Shaded View on Fashion: \"SARKO TAYLOR BAR\" with Anita Sarko & Scott Taylor on SiriusXM CHANNEL 28 THE SPECTRUM Saturdays @ 11pm PST 2am EST |publisher=Dianepernet.typepad.com |date=June 1, 2013 |accessdate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713113100/http://dianepernet.typepad.com/diane/2013/06/sarko-taylor-bar-with-anita-sarko-scott-taylor-on-siriusxm-channel-28-the-spectrum-saturdays-11pm-ps.html |archivedate=July 13, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===Live performances===\nIn 2005, motivated by the [[invasion of Iraq]], she began internationally performing live new unreleased music, including the DFA release of the anti\u2013war song \"Bullet Proof\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.factmag.com/2010/03/19/ray-mang-disco-sizzler-for-dfa-with-vocals-from-deee-lites-lady-miss-kier/ |title=Ray Mang disco sizzler for DFA, with vocals from Deee-Lite's Lady Miss Kier \u2013 FACT Magazine: Music News, New Music |publisher=Factmag.com |date=March 19, 2010 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref>\nShe has headlined numerous festivals and gay pride events as well as opened for [[James Brown]]'s last tour at the Good Vibrations festival in Australia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.starobserver.com.au/features/entertainment-features/entertainment-play/groove-is-still-in-her-art/71827 |title=Groove is still in her art |work=Star Observer |accessdate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713045142/http://www.starobserver.com.au/features/entertainment-features/entertainment-play/groove-is-still-in-her-art/71827 |archivedate=July 13, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Style and fashion icon==\nIn 1990, she was on the cover of ''Vogue''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leblow.co.uk/60s-fashion-in-the-90s-deee-lite/lady-miss-kier-vogue-italia-1990/ |title=Lady Miss Kier Vogue Italia 1990 \u2013 Le Blow |publisher=Leblow.co.uk |date=October 27, 2013 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> In 1991, when designer Emilio Pucci was given a lifetime achievement award from CFDA Fashion Awards, she was asked to star in the tribute video.<ref>{{Citation|title=Lady Kier from dee-lite + Pal Joey '91 'Pucci u say love?'|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3MqDWOIFLcU|via=YouTube|accessdate = January 17, 2007}}</ref> In 2010, ''Elle'' named her one of Music's 25 Most Influential Style Icons with [[Grace Jones]], [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Debbie Harry]], and [[M.I.A. (rapper)|MIA]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Bailey |first=Alyssa |url=http://www.elle.com/fashion/spotlight/fashion-high-notes-446376#slide-17 |title=Influential Women in Music \u2013 Influential Musicians |work=Elle |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> In 2010, ''Glamour'' named Lady Miss Kier as one of the Top Influential Music Style Icons with [[Rihanna]], [[Lady Gaga]], and [[Gwen Stefani]].<ref>{{cite web|last=David |first=Jessica |url=http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/fashion/celebrity-fashion/2010/08/influential-style-icons-in-music-madonna-rihanna-lady-gaga-the-runaways#!image-number=10 |title=The 25 Most Influential Style Icons in Music &#124; Celebrity Fashion and Style Pictures (Glamour.com UK) |publisher=Glamourmagazine.co.uk |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> In 2012, ''Vogue'' quoted her experience with [[John Fluevog]] and the rise of \"The Munster,\" which was made famous as a symbol of the 1990s house/club underground DJ scene.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fluevog.com/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110181730/http://www.fluevog.com/files_2/press-release_041510_web.html|url-status=dead|title=Fluevog Shoes &#124; Unique Shoes for Men and Women|archivedate=January 10, 2014|website=Fluevog Shoes}}</ref> Additionally, Fluevog credits her as the reason the shoe shot to popularity on its website's company history timeline, and credit her as the reason its company was successful.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Fluevog Shoes {{!}} About John Fluevog|url = https://www.fluevog.com/our-story/about-fluevog/|accessdate = October 5, 2015}}</ref> As related, Vice Magazine noted that \"Indeed, Lady Miss Kier's taste for the massive John Fluevog platform shoes she famously wore on their first album cover helped propel the early 90s into a 70s fashion revival\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thump.vice.com/en_us/article/ez8jd7/dee-lite-good-beat-time-travel|title=Experience Dee-Lite's \"Holographic Mind Orgy\"|date=December 17, 2013|work=Thump|access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref> In 2012, Rookie Mag wrote about her status as a style icon and the same year<ref>{{Cite web|title = Secret Style Icon: Lady Miss Kier \u2013 Rookie|url = http://www.rookiemag.com/2012/09/secret-style-icon-lady-miss-kier/|accessdate = October 5, 2015}}</ref> respected shoe designer Jerome Rousseau named a shoe inspired by her after the singer. The shoe was called \"Kier Iredescent\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shopbop.com/kier-iredescent-high-heel-sandals/vp/v=1/845524441950778.htm |title=Jerome C. Rousseau Kier Iridescent Sandals |publisher=Shopbop |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, ''W'' cited Lady Miss Kier with [[Chlo\u00eb Sevigny]] and [[Twiggy]] as current fashion influences. Also in 2013, ''Ladygunn'' magazine featured a full spread on the singer in its Legends issue<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ladygunn.com/people/lady-miss-kier |title=Lady Miss Kier |publisher=Ladygunn |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> and she was asked by Kenzo to be the performer for its Paris Fashion week party.<ref name=\"vmagazine.com\" /> From 2007 to 2012, the house of Mugler used her song for its website campaign.<ref>{{cite web|last=Musto |first=Michael |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,305743,00.html |title=Designers' celebrity muses |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=March 5, 1993 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/nme-video/youtube/id/3MqDWOIFLcU |title=Free Music Videos, Video Interviews, Music Video News, Live Sessions and Clips |work=NME |accessdate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110183205/http://www.nme.com/nme-video/youtube/id/3MqDWOIFLcU |archivedate=January 10, 2014 }}</ref> In 2015, she was referenced in ''The Guardian'' as an inspiration for designer Jeremy Scott's Fall 2016 line, which debuted at New York Fashion Week.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Jeremy Scott at New York fashion week: 60s pop culture through an 80s prism|url = https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2015/sep/14/jeremy-scott-new-york-fashion-week|website = The Guardian|accessdate = October 5, 2015|first = Lauren Cochrane in New|last = York}}</ref> In 2015, Essie nail polish brand released a pink polish inspired by her, called Groove Is in the Heart, described as \"don't stop 'til you get enough! this wildly happy peachy pink neon is ready to rave all night long\".<ref>{{Cite web|title = groove is in the heart by essie|url = http://www.essie.com/colors/pinks/groove-is-in-the-heart.aspx|website = Essie|accessdate = October 5, 2015}}</ref> In 2015, Givenchy's Milan Fashion Week show drew inspiration from her, borrowing a lyric from her ''World Clique'' album song \"Power of Love\", using the line \"I believe in the power of love\" as part of how it branded the debut of its Fall 2016 line.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://fashionista.com/2015/09/givenchy-party-milan-fashion-week|title = Here's What Went Down at Givenchy's Insane Milan Fashion Week Party|date = September 26, 2015|website = |last = Mau|first = Dhani}}</ref> In 2016, ''Vogue'' Magazine interviewed Lady Miss Kier, calling her a \"Club Kid Icon,\" referencing how world class designers know her as a \"legend and a lady,\" highlighting how designers such as Thierry Mugler have borrowed from her look.<ref name=\"Vogue\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/lady-miss-kier-industry-icons-club-kid-icon|title='90s Club-Kid Icon Lady Miss Kier on Her Latest Fashion Obsessions|work=Vogue|access-date=July 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Movies and books==\nHer music has been used in a multitude of films, including ''[[The Heat (film)|The Heat]]'' (2013),{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} ''House of Versace'' (2013),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://capsuleshow.com/wearethemarket/mr-dool-reviews-house-of-versace-and-isnt-pleased/ |title=Capsule Show |publisher=Capsule Show |accessdate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402123540/http://capsuleshow.com/wearethemarket/mr-dool-reviews-house-of-versace-and-isnt-pleased/ |archivedate=April 2, 2015 }}</ref> ''[[Crazy Sexy Cool: The TLC Story]]'' (2013),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/7410-vh1s-tlc-biopic-was-worth-the-watch-worth-the-tears |title=Bustle |publisher=Bustle |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Charlie's Angels (2000 film)|Charlie's Angels]]'' (2000),{{citation needed|date=March 2014}} [[Wigstock]] (1995), ''[[Party Girl (1995 film)|Party Girl]]'' (1995), ''[[Dumb and Dumber]]'' (1994), ''Charlie's Angels (2000),'' ''I Now Pronounce you Chuck and Larry (2007)'' and numerous TV series episodes including ''Britain's Got More Talent, The Voice, RuPaul's Drag Race, American Crime Story, Coronation Street, Transparent, Misfits, Hello Ladies, The Heat, New Girl, How I Met Your Mother, It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia, Private Practice, License to Wed, Dancing with the Stars, What Love is, Down to You, Lost & Found, Can't Hardly Wait, Bill Nye the Science Guy, The War Room'', ''Beavis and Butt-Head, and Big Mouth.''{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nIn 2018, the Netflix series [[Big Mouth (TV series)|''Big Mouth'']] released a [[Planned Parenthood]] and Deee-lite themed episode<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tv.avclub.com/nick-kroll-on-how-a-talk-by-planned-parenthood-led-to-b-1829562016|title=Nick Kroll on how a talk by Planned Parenthood led to Big Mouth's boldest episode yet|last=Adams|first=Erik|work=TV Club|access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref>\u2014relatedly, Lady Miss Kier has been a longtime pro-choice advocate and safe sex was a theme in Deee-lite's music. In 1995, Lady Kier was featured in ''[[Wigstock: The Movie]]'', which included live footage of her performing and a song on the soundtrack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.last.fm/music/Lady+Miss+Kier/_/Touch+Me+With+Your+Sunshine |title=Lady Miss Kier \u2013 Touch Me With Your Sunshine \u2013 Listen and discover music at |publisher=Last.fm |date=November 26, 2013 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> In 2001 she was included in ''Summer Love: The Rave-umentary''.<ref>[http://www.fandango.com/ladymisskier/overview/p543760 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110193855/http://www.fandango.com/ladymisskier/overview/p543760 |date=January 10, 2014 }}</ref> In 2005, Lady Miss Kier was the featured artist on the podcast ''Ron-Kat-Delic Show''. Her words also were shared through a number of published books, including ''Verbal Abuse \u2013 No 3'' by Chi Chi Valenti,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mothernyc.com/verbal/ |title=Verbal Abuse Magazine \u2013 Dispatches From the Nightclub Literati |publisher=Mothernyc.com |date=February 8, 2007 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> ''Creative Time: The Book: 33 Years of Public Art in New York'' by Anne Pasternak,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Odd_News/2002/06/25/Today-in-Music-A-look-back-at-pop-music/UPI-42021025000319/ |title=Today in Music: A look back at pop music |agency=United Press International |date=June 25, 2002 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> ''Creative License: The Law and Culture of Digital Sampling'' by Kembrew McLeod and Peter DiCola<ref>{{cite web|url=http://futureofmusic.org/events/creative-license-book-release |title=Creative License Book Release &#124; Future of Music Coalition |publisher=Futureofmusic.org |date=February 26, 2011 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> and ''All Music Guide to Electronica: The Definitive Guide to Electronic Music'' by Vladimir Bogdanov.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GJNXLSBlL7IC&pg=PT74&lpg=PT74&dq=1995+apple+conference+lady+miss+kier&source=bl&ots=R84zz4nCme&sig=G5o7xcPanNCaWguhcV-mzXpRF2w&hl=en&sa=X&ei=fM3BUsjXLM23sAT2l4CQDw&ved=0CGUQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=1995%20apple%20conference%20lady%20miss%20kier&f=false |title=All Music Guide to Electronica: The Definitive Guide to Electronic Music \u2013 Vladimir Bogdanov \u2013 Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Panels and appearances==\nLady Miss Kier has spoken at Princeton University's \"Youth Music and Youth Culture\",<ref>{{cite news|last=Powers |first=Ann |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/11/24/arts/in-theory-and-practice-defining-youth-music.html |title=In Theory and Practice, Defining Youth Music |work=The New York Times |date=November 24, 1992 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> [[Cooper Union]]'s multimedia presentation \"Hiccup\" in 1993, Apple's 1995 \"Future Arts Panel\" with [[Peter Gabriel]] and [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] founder, [[John Perry Barlow]], George Washington University's Law School Summit [[Future of Music Coalition]] in 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.futureofmusic.org/newsletter/fmc-newsletter-60-september-6-2007 |title=FMC Newsletter No. 60 &#124; Future of Music Coalition |publisher=Futureofmusic.org |date=July 8, 2015 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> and New York University's \"NYU Panel Nelson Sullivan: Vlogging in the 80s\" in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2013/04/09/fales-hosts-a-panel-discussion-nelson-sullivan-vlogging-in-the-80s-april-25.html|title=NYU Fales Library Hosts A Panel Discussion Nelson Sullivan Vlogging in the 80s|publisher=Nyu.edu|accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> In 2013 she was featured in an exhibit entitled \"NYC 1993\", which was presented through New York City's [[New Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newmuseum.org/exhibitions/view/nyc-1993-experimental-jet-set-trash-and-no-star |title=NYC 1993: Experimental Jet Set, Trash and No Star |publisher=New Museum |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> Beyond the installation, her voice recording was played via pay phones throughout the New York area. In 2013, Lady Miss Kier was the featured voiceover artist in The Jazz Foundation of America's animated promo for the event \"A Great Night in Harlem.\"<ref>[http://jazzfoundation.org/Apollo2014] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140815003727/http://jazzfoundation.org/Apollo2014 |date=August 15, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Yn8-WjVkpFk |title=A Great Night in Harlem: Animated Promo |via=YouTube |date=April 25, 2013 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==''Space Channel 5'' and lawsuit==\nIn 2003, Kirby sued video game company [[Sega]], claiming that the character of \"[[Space Channel 5#Characters|Ulala]]\" in its [[Dreamcast]] game ''[[Space Channel 5]]'' was an unauthorized use of her likeness.<ref name=lawsuit>{{cite web|url=http://www.ladykier.com/segacase.htm |title=Lady Kier VS Sega |publisher=Ladykier.com |accessdate=December 11, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061206003216/http://ladykier.com/segacase.htm |archivedate=December 6, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Kirby claimed that Sega offered to pay her {{USD|16,000}} to license her name, image and songs for the game, though she rejected its offer. Kirby alleged that the video game maker later used her resemblance anyway (including the name Ulala \u2013 referencing Kirby's signature phrase \"Ooh la la\" in her recorded and live performances), at which point she initiated the lawsuit. She ultimately lost the suit.<ref name=lawsuit2>{{cite court | litigants=Kirby v. Sega | court=Court of Appeal of California, 2nd District, Div. 8 | date=September 25, 2006 | accessdate=August 30, 2016 | url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=3191814113989354720&q=%2250+Cal.Rptr.3d+607&hl=en&as_sdt=2002 | }}</ref>\n\n==Political views and activism==\nLady Kier used her popularity as a platform to promote a variety of causes and is widely known not only as a singer, DJ, and fashion icon, but also as a social, environmental, and human rights activist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ocweekly.com/illustrated-homage-to-deee-lites-lady-miss-kier-7925215/|title=Illustrated Homage To Deee-Lite's Lady Miss Kier|date=February 24, 2017|work=OC Weekly|access-date=July 12, 2018}}</ref> She is a vocal advocate for LGBTQ rights and a longtime celebrated ally of the LGBTQ community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grownasslady.com/2014/05/27/style-icon-lady-miss-kier/|title=Style Icon: Lady Miss Kier \u00ab Grown Ass Lady|website=grownasslady.com|access-date=July 12, 2018}}</ref> As such, she is frequently invited to host, perform, MC, and DJ gay pride parades and associated events internationally.<ref>{{Citation|last=Mikey Sin|title=Mayor Rob Ford calls Lady Miss Kier (Deee-lite) at Pride Toronto|date=July 4, 2012|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pOOoB-COUsk|access-date=July 12, 2018}}</ref> She is staunchly pro-abortion rights and is a women's rights advocate, was featured in TV informercial promoting pro-abortion rights political action \"The Most Exciting Women in Music\" alongside [[Corina (singer)|Corina]], [[Juliet Cuming]], [[Kim Gordon]] ([[Sonic Youth]]), [[MC Lyte]], [[Kate Pierson]] ([[The B-52's]]), [[Crystal Waters]], [[Tina Weymouth]] ([[Talking Heads]], [[Tom Tom Club]]) in 1991.<ref>{{Citation|last=CheeseFoodProduct|title=The Most Exciting Women in Music|date=November 7, 2011|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qUMLLsQozMg|access-date=July 12, 2018}}</ref> In 1991, Lady Miss Kier was an award presenter at The Reebok Human Rights Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bkhonline.com/the-reebook-human-rights-awards/|title=The Reebok Human Rights Awards &#124; Black History|date=March 16, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nA strong supporter of environmental causes, her album \"Infinity Within\" was the first CD ever released using eco-pak packaging, cutting the amount of plastic used by half. A portion of the album's profits was pledged to Greenpeace and she was recognized for her efforts with an environmental media award from the World Wildlife Fund.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.studio-nibble.com/cd/index.php?title=Eco-Pak|title=Eco-Pak \u2013 cdHistory|website=studio-nibble.com|access-date=July 12, 2018}}</ref> As part of her environmental activism, she called attention to the issue of [[ozone depletion]] on the Deee-lite album ''Infinity Within'' with her song \"I Had a Dream I Was Falling Through a Hole in the Ozone Layer\"<ref>{{Citation|title=Deee-Lite \u2013 I Had a Dream I Was Falling Through a Hole in the Ozone Layer|url=https://genius.com/Deee-lite-i-had-a-dream-i-was-falling-through-a-hole-in-the-ozone-layer-lyrics|access-date=July 12, 2018}}</ref> and ''Vogue'' Magazine has highlighted her \"interest in supporting environmental causes\".<ref name=\"Vogue\" /> She is an anti-war activist and in 2010, she released a new version of the P-Funk track \"Bullet Proof\" with Ray Mang with lyrics calling attention to the perils of war and denouncing global militarization after the song was featured in 2005 during her world tour.<ref>{{Citation|last=WestSavannah|title=Ray Mang (featuring Lady Kier) \u2013 Bulletproof|date=February 2, 2010|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cZFxHc_Jwco|access-date=July 12, 2018}}</ref> She is a longtime leader in getting out the vote and encouraging Americans to register to vote. Her music video \"Vote Baby Vote\" was featured for MTV's \"Rock The Vote\" in 1992 and was highlighted by Rolling Stone Magazine as one of the top \"ten major moments in rock the vote history\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/pictures/10-major-moments-in-rock-the-vote-history-20160712/deee-lites-vote-baby-vote-1992-20160711|title=10 Major Moments in Rock the Vote History|last=Runtagh|first=Jordan|date=July 12, 2016|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=July 12, 2018}}</ref> During the 2016 U.S. Presidential election, she ultimately voted for [[Green Party of the United States|Green Party]] candidate [[Jill Stein]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Deeeeeelite/posts/10154530170449717 |title=Lady Miss Kier |publisher=Facebook }}{{Primary source inline|date=January 2020}}</ref> but was an outspoken and enthusiastic supporter of Bernie Sanders. To promote Bernie Sanders, she hosted an art exhibit at Hole Gallery in New York City and a fundraiser called \"Bernin' Up NYC\" to rally supporters get out the vote.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://gothamist.com/2016/04/01/bernie_sanders_bronx_rally.php#photo-14|title=Bernie in the Bronx: \"If We Win NY We Are Going To Make It To The White House!\"|work=Gothamist|access-date=July 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829111721/http://gothamist.com/2016/04/01/bernie_sanders_bronx_rally.php#photo-14|archive-date=August 29, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Official Website}}\n*[http://www.discogs.com/artist/Deee-Lite Deee-Lite Discography]\n*{{IMDb name|1398296}}\n\n{{Deee-Lite}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kier, Lady Miss}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American dance musicians]]\n[[Category:American female songwriters]]\n[[Category:American pop musicians]]\n[[Category:American house musicians]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:Club DJs]]\n[[Category:American female DJs]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Youngstown, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Fashion Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Singers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Deee-Lite members]]\n[[Category:American women in electronic music]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:American hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:American female hip hop musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Lead too short|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| image           = Lady Miss Kier by Bobby Miller.jpg\n| name            = Lady Miss Kier\n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| background      = solo_singer\n| birth_name      = Kierin Magenta Kirby\n| alias           = Lady Kier, Kier Kirby\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1963|8|15}}\n| birth_place     = [[Youngstown, Ohio]], U.S.\n| origin          = New York City\n| instrument      = Vocals\n| genre           = {{flatlist|\n*[[Electronica]]\n*[[dance-pop]]\n*[[House music|house]]\n*[[Hip hop music|hip hop]]}}\n| occupation      = Singer, songwriter, DJ, [[record producer|producer]]\n| years_active    = 1986\u2013present\n| label           = [[Elektra Records|Elektra]]<br />Pluto Moon\n| associated_acts = [[Deee-Lite]]\n| website         = {{URL|ladykier.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Kierin Magenta Kirby''' (born August 15, 1963), better known as '''Lady Miss Kier''', is an American singer, songwriter, DJ, designer, fashion icon, and activist. She was the vocalist for the band [[Deee-Lite]], followed by a career as a DJ and solo songwriter. She is also known widely for her social, environmental, and human-rights activism.\n\n==Music career==\n===Deee-Lite===\nIn 1986, Kirby met Ukrainian-born Dmitry Brill (\"Supa DJ Dmitry\") in New York, when she made him silver platform boots and a glitter blue spacesuit for his band, Shazork. That same year, she began experimenting with singing and writing music with Brill.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldies.com/artist-biography/Deee-Lite.html|title=Deee-Lite Biography: OLDIES.com|publisher=Oldies.com |accessdate=April 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nShortly after their first show in 1986, Brill was introduced to [[Towa Tei]], a Japan-raised Korean DJ who Kirby and Brill invited to join the band several years later. Combining Kirby's vocal and writing talents with Brill's sampling skills and Tei's techno mixing, the three formed the band [[Deee-Lite]]. They had performances every month, with Kier designing new costumes for each one. When the band signed a seven-album deal with [[Elektra Records]] she stopped go-go dancing, which she previously had continued to do at Bentleys and The Copa.\n\nDeee-Lite's sound was a mix of [[house music|house]], [[techno]] and [[Electronic dance music|dance]] elements. Deee-Lite shot to stardom in 1990 with the release of their first album ''[[World Clique]]'' and the hit \"[[Groove Is in the Heart]]\". In [[1991 MTV Video Music Awards|1991]], MTV nominated Deee-Lite for several Video Music Awards, including Video of the Year, Best Dance Video, Best New Artist, Best Breakthrough Video, and Best Editing in a Video.\n\nKirby was very involved in the band's output: writing, producing, and performing the bulk of the band's songs. Known as much for their outrageous personae and costumes as for their music, the three took on larger-than-life alter-egos: Super DJ Dmitri, Jungle DJ Towa Towa, and Lady Miss Kier. Kirby is credited with designing and creating the look of the band, as well as much of the artwork accompanying the band's albums and marketing material. Her initial look relied on revamped and exaggerated retro '60s fashions. Her signature look was a zip-up catsuit, platform shoes and flipped hair-do.\n\nDeee-Lite followed their successful first album with ''[[Infinity Within]]'', a politically charged second album, in 1992. Their third album ''[[Dewdrops in the Garden]]'' was released in 1994 and saw a return to house roots with a new, more naturalistic tone.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} Neither of the two follow-up albums matched the commercial success of their debut. The second and third albums were hampered by difficulties with the label, which refused to promote, support touring, or fund contractual videos.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} The band functionally broke up during the writing of their third album in 1993, but Kirby and Brill decided to finish the project and tour together to promote the album before going their separate ways. In 1996, a remix album was released, and a greatest hits album was released in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/gig-reviews/lady-miss-kier/2006/02/13/1139679507664.html |title=Lady Miss Kier \u2013 Gig Reviews \u2013 Music \u2013 Entertainment|work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=February 13, 2006 |accessdate=November 13, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===International DJ and songwriting solo career===\n[[File:Lady Miss Kier.jpg|thumb|Lady Miss Kier performing in 2007]]\nBrill and Kirby's relationship fractured, and Deee-lite disbanded in 1995.<ref name=\"Smh.com.au\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/gig-reviews/lady-miss-kier/2006/02/13/1139679507664.html?page=2 |title=Lady Miss Kier \u2013 Gig Reviews \u2013 Music \u2013 Entertainment|work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=February 13, 2006 |accessdate=November 13, 2008}}</ref> \"When Dmitry and I split up, that was the end of the band,\" Kirby said. \"It was sad because I loved the band. I didn't want to leave the band and the music and I missed my writing partner, but we couldn't get along.\"<ref name=\"Smh.com.au\"/>\n\nIn 1995, after quitting the band, Lady Miss Kier moved to London where she began touring as a deejay and learning the technical end of production, recording, and engineering. In the late 1990s, she collaborated on the albums of [[Bootsy Collins]], I Kamanchi and [[A Guy Called Gerald]]. In 2002, she contributed an exclusive solo track called \"I'm Not Staying at Home\" to the compilation ''Straight Up & Dirty''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/4444-Lady-Kier |title=Lady Kier Discography |publisher=discogs |date=August 15, 1963 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> Since going solo, she has featured and co-written with artists such as Full Cycle, [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]], Junie Morrison, A Guy Called Gerald, Apollo Heights, and several P-Funk luminaries. Outside of the studio, she continued to showcase her live performances with new material for various music, film, and art festivals, as well as headlining numerous Gay Pride events worldwide. In 2012 she began performing a Deee-Lite tribute for various occasions, including the 2013 Paris Fashion Week for [[Kenzo]]<ref name=\"vmagazine.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vmagazine.com/site/content/758/party-with-kenzo |title=V Magazine / Party With Kenzo |publisher=Vmagazine.com |accessdate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816090846/http://www.vmagazine.com/site/content/758/party-with-kenzo |archivedate=August 16, 2015 }}</ref> as well as a tribute to legendary NYC DJ [[Mark Kamins]] at Santos Party House.<ref>{{cite web|last=Augustin |first=Camille |url=http://www.vibe.com/photo-gallery/everybody-celebrates-mark-kamins-santos-party-house-tribute-tonight |title=\"Everybody\" Celebrates Mark Kamins at Santos Tribute Tonight |work=Vibe |date=April 17, 2013 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs a DJ, she has spun internationally for over 17 years at thousands of clubs and major festivals including [[Coachella Festival]] (2007),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coachellarecordings.com/sources.cfm?bandid=561&year=2007 |title=Lady Miss Kier \u2013 Coachella 2007 |publisher=Coachella Recordings |date=April 28, 2007 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> Berlin's Berghain (2010)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://berghain.de/event/162 |title=Berghain Berlin &#124; Programm: 31 December 2010 |publisher=Berghain.de |date=December 31, 2010 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> and Sydney Mardi Gras (2012),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samesame.com.au/news/7619/Heres-Mardi-Gras-2012 |title=Here's Mardi Gras 2012! |publisher=Samesame.com.au |accessdate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924094037/http://www.samesame.com.au/news/7619/Heres-Mardi-Gras-2012 |archivedate=September 24, 2015 }}</ref> as well as radio programs such as East Village Radio<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eastvillageradio.com/content/content.php?id=6192 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 10, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110183059/http://www.eastvillageradio.com/content/content.php?id=6192 |archivedate=January 10, 2014 }}</ref> and Sirius XM.<ref>{{cite web |last=Belverio |first=Glenn |url=http://dianepernet.typepad.com/diane/2013/06/sarko-taylor-bar-with-anita-sarko-scott-taylor-on-siriusxm-channel-28-the-spectrum-saturdays-11pm-ps.html |title=Diane, A Shaded View on Fashion: \"SARKO TAYLOR BAR\" with Anita Sarko & Scott Taylor on SiriusXM CHANNEL 28 THE SPECTRUM Saturdays @ 11pm PST 2am EST |publisher=Dianepernet.typepad.com |date=June 1, 2013 |accessdate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713113100/http://dianepernet.typepad.com/diane/2013/06/sarko-taylor-bar-with-anita-sarko-scott-taylor-on-siriusxm-channel-28-the-spectrum-saturdays-11pm-ps.html |archivedate=July 13, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===Live performances===\nIn 2005, motivated by the [[invasion of Iraq]], she began internationally performing live new unreleased music, including the DFA release of the anti\u2013war song \"Bullet Proof\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.factmag.com/2010/03/19/ray-mang-disco-sizzler-for-dfa-with-vocals-from-deee-lites-lady-miss-kier/ |title=Ray Mang disco sizzler for DFA, with vocals from Deee-Lite's Lady Miss Kier \u2013 FACT Magazine: Music News, New Music |publisher=Factmag.com |date=March 19, 2010 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref>\nShe has headlined numerous festivals and gay pride events as well as opened for [[James Brown]]'s last tour at the Good Vibrations festival in Australia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.starobserver.com.au/features/entertainment-features/entertainment-play/groove-is-still-in-her-art/71827 |title=Groove is still in her art |work=Star Observer |accessdate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713045142/http://www.starobserver.com.au/features/entertainment-features/entertainment-play/groove-is-still-in-her-art/71827 |archivedate=July 13, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Style and fashion icon==\nIn 1990, she was on the cover of ''Vogue''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leblow.co.uk/60s-fashion-in-the-90s-deee-lite/lady-miss-kier-vogue-italia-1990/ |title=Lady Miss Kier Vogue Italia 1990 \u2013 Le Blow |publisher=Leblow.co.uk |date=October 27, 2013 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> In 1991, when designer Emilio Pucci was given a lifetime achievement award from CFDA Fashion Awards, she was asked to star in the tribute video.<ref>{{Citation|title=Lady Kier from dee-lite + Pal Joey '91 'Pucci u say love?'|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3MqDWOIFLcU|via=YouTube|accessdate = January 17, 2007}}</ref> In 2010, ''Elle'' named her one of Music's 25 Most Influential Style Icons with [[Grace Jones]], [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Debbie Harry]], and [[M.I.A. (rapper)|MIA]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Bailey |first=Alyssa |url=http://www.elle.com/fashion/spotlight/fashion-high-notes-446376#slide-17 |title=Influential Women in Music \u2013 Influential Musicians |work=Elle |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> In 2010, ''Glamour'' named Lady Miss Kier as one of the Top Influential Music Style Icons with [[Rihanna]], [[Lady Gaga]], and [[Gwen Stefani]].<ref>{{cite web|last=David |first=Jessica |url=http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/fashion/celebrity-fashion/2010/08/influential-style-icons-in-music-madonna-rihanna-lady-gaga-the-runaways#!image-number=10 |title=The 25 Most Influential Style Icons in Music &#124; Celebrity Fashion and Style Pictures (Glamour.com UK) |publisher=Glamourmagazine.co.uk |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> In 2012, ''Vogue'' quoted her experience with [[John Fluevog]] and the rise of \"The Munster,\" which was made famous as a symbol of the 1990s house/club underground DJ scene.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fluevog.com/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110181730/http://www.fluevog.com/files_2/press-release_041510_web.html|url-status=dead|title=Fluevog Shoes &#124; Unique Shoes for Men and Women|archivedate=January 10, 2014|website=Fluevog Shoes}}</ref> Additionally, Fluevog credits her as the reason the shoe shot to popularity on its website's company history timeline, and credit her as the reason its company was successful.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Fluevog Shoes {{!}} About John Fluevog|url = https://www.fluevog.com/our-story/about-fluevog/|accessdate = October 5, 2015}}</ref> As related, Vice Magazine noted that \"Indeed, Lady Miss Kier's taste for the massive John Fluevog platform shoes she famously wore on their first album cover helped propel the early 90s into a 70s fashion revival\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thump.vice.com/en_us/article/ez8jd7/dee-lite-good-beat-time-travel|title=Experience Dee-Lite's \"Holographic Mind Orgy\"|date=December 17, 2013|work=Thump|access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref> In 2012, Rookie Mag wrote about her status as a style icon and the same year<ref>{{Cite web|title = Secret Style Icon: Lady Miss Kier \u2013 Rookie|url = http://www.rookiemag.com/2012/09/secret-style-icon-lady-miss-kier/|accessdate = October 5, 2015}}</ref> respected shoe designer Jerome Rousseau named a shoe inspired by her after the singer. The shoe was called \"Kier Iredescent\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shopbop.com/kier-iredescent-high-heel-sandals/vp/v=1/845524441950778.htm |title=Jerome C. Rousseau Kier Iridescent Sandals |publisher=Shopbop |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, ''W'' cited Lady Miss Kier with [[Chlo\u00eb Sevigny]] and [[Twiggy]] as current fashion influences. Also in 2013, ''Ladygunn'' magazine featured a full spread on the singer in its Legends issue<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ladygunn.com/people/lady-miss-kier |title=Lady Miss Kier |publisher=Ladygunn |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> and she was asked by Kenzo to be the performer for its Paris Fashion week party.<ref name=\"vmagazine.com\" /> From 2007 to 2012, the house of Mugler used her song for its website campaign.<ref>{{cite web|last=Musto |first=Michael |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,305743,00.html |title=Designers' celebrity muses |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=March 5, 1993 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/nme-video/youtube/id/3MqDWOIFLcU |title=Free Music Videos, Video Interviews, Music Video News, Live Sessions and Clips |work=NME |accessdate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110183205/http://www.nme.com/nme-video/youtube/id/3MqDWOIFLcU |archivedate=January 10, 2014 }}</ref> In 2015, she was referenced in ''The Guardian'' as an inspiration for designer Jeremy Scott's Fall 2016 line, which debuted at New York Fashion Week.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Jeremy Scott at New York fashion week: 60s pop culture through an 80s prism|url = https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2015/sep/14/jeremy-scott-new-york-fashion-week|website = The Guardian|accessdate = October 5, 2015|first = Lauren Cochrane in New|last = York}}</ref> In 2015, Essie nail polish brand released a pink polish inspired by her, called Groove Is in the Heart, described as \"don't stop 'til you get enough! this wildly happy peachy pink neon is ready to rave all night long\".<ref>{{Cite web|title = groove is in the heart by essie|url = http://www.essie.com/colors/pinks/groove-is-in-the-heart.aspx|website = Essie|accessdate = October 5, 2015}}</ref> In 2015, Givenchy's Milan Fashion Week show drew inspiration from her, borrowing a lyric from her ''World Clique'' album song \"Power of Love\", using the line \"I believe in the power of love\" as part of how it branded the debut of its Fall 2016 line.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://fashionista.com/2015/09/givenchy-party-milan-fashion-week|title = Here's What Went Down at Givenchy's Insane Milan Fashion Week Party|date = September 26, 2015|website = |last = Mau|first = Dhani}}</ref> In 2016, ''Vogue'' Magazine interviewed Lady Miss Kier, calling her a \"Club Kid Icon,\" referencing how world class designers know her as a \"legend and a lady,\" highlighting how designers such as Thierry Mugler have borrowed from her look.<ref name=\"Vogue\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/lady-miss-kier-industry-icons-club-kid-icon|title='90s Club-Kid Icon Lady Miss Kier on Her Latest Fashion Obsessions|work=Vogue|access-date=July 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Movies and books==\nHer music has been used in a multitude of films, including ''[[The Heat (film)|The Heat]]'' (2013),{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} ''House of Versace'' (2013),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://capsuleshow.com/wearethemarket/mr-dool-reviews-house-of-versace-and-isnt-pleased/ |title=Capsule Show |publisher=Capsule Show |accessdate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402123540/http://capsuleshow.com/wearethemarket/mr-dool-reviews-house-of-versace-and-isnt-pleased/ |archivedate=April 2, 2015 }}</ref> ''[[Crazy Sexy Cool: The TLC Story]]'' (2013),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/7410-vh1s-tlc-biopic-was-worth-the-watch-worth-the-tears |title=Bustle |publisher=Bustle |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Charlie's Angels (2000 film)|Charlie's Angels]]'' (2000),{{citation needed|date=March 2014}} [[Wigstock]] (1995), ''[[Party Girl (1995 film)|Party Girl]]'' (1995), ''[[Dumb and Dumber]]'' (1994), ''Charlie's Angels (2000),'' ''I Now Pronounce you Chuck and Larry (2007)'' and numerous TV series episodes including ''Britain's Got More Talent, The Voice, RuPaul's Drag Race, American Crime Story, Coronation Street, Transparent, Misfits, Hello Ladies, The Heat, New Girl, How I Met Your Mother, It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia, Private Practice, License to Wed, Dancing with the Stars, What Love is, Down to You, Lost & Found, Can't Hardly Wait, Bill Nye the Science Guy, The War Room'', ''Beavis and Butt-Head, and Big Mouth.''{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nIn 2018, the Netflix series [[Big Mouth (TV series)|''Big Mouth'']] released a [[Planned Parenthood]] and Deee-lite themed episode<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tv.avclub.com/nick-kroll-on-how-a-talk-by-planned-parenthood-led-to-b-1829562016|title=Nick Kroll on how a talk by Planned Parenthood led to Big Mouth's boldest episode yet|last=Adams|first=Erik|work=TV Club|access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref>\u2014relatedly, Lady Miss Kier has been a longtime pro-choice advocate and safe sex was a theme in Deee-lite's music. In 1995, Lady Kier was featured in ''[[Wigstock: The Movie]]'', which included live footage of her performing and a song on the soundtrack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.last.fm/music/Lady+Miss+Kier/_/Touch+Me+With+Your+Sunshine |title=Lady Miss Kier \u2013 Touch Me With Your Sunshine \u2013 Listen and discover music at |publisher=Last.fm |date=November 26, 2013 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> In 2001 she was included in ''Summer Love: The Rave-umentary''.<ref>[http://www.fandango.com/ladymisskier/overview/p543760 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110193855/http://www.fandango.com/ladymisskier/overview/p543760 |date=January 10, 2014 }}</ref> In 2005, Lady Miss Kier was the featured artist on the podcast ''Ron-Kat-Delic Show''. Her words also were shared through a number of published books, including ''Verbal Abuse \u2013 No 3'' by Chi Chi Valenti,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mothernyc.com/verbal/ |title=Verbal Abuse Magazine \u2013 Dispatches From the Nightclub Literati |publisher=Mothernyc.com |date=February 8, 2007 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> ''Creative Time: The Book: 33 Years of Public Art in New York'' by Anne Pasternak,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Odd_News/2002/06/25/Today-in-Music-A-look-back-at-pop-music/UPI-42021025000319/ |title=Today in Music: A look back at pop music |agency=United Press International |date=June 25, 2002 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> ''Creative License: The Law and Culture of Digital Sampling'' by Kembrew McLeod and Peter DiCola<ref>{{cite web|url=http://futureofmusic.org/events/creative-license-book-release |title=Creative License Book Release &#124; Future of Music Coalition |publisher=Futureofmusic.org |date=February 26, 2011 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> and ''All Music Guide to Electronica: The Definitive Guide to Electronic Music'' by Vladimir Bogdanov.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GJNXLSBlL7IC&pg=PT74&lpg=PT74&dq=1995+apple+conference+lady+miss+kier&source=bl&ots=R84zz4nCme&sig=G5o7xcPanNCaWguhcV-mzXpRF2w&hl=en&sa=X&ei=fM3BUsjXLM23sAT2l4CQDw&ved=0CGUQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=1995%20apple%20conference%20lady%20miss%20kier&f=false |title=All Music Guide to Electronica: The Definitive Guide to Electronic Music \u2013 Vladimir Bogdanov \u2013 Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Panels and appearances==\nLady Miss Kier has spoken at Princeton University's \"Youth Music and Youth Culture\",<ref>{{cite news|last=Powers |first=Ann |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/11/24/arts/in-theory-and-practice-defining-youth-music.html |title=In Theory and Practice, Defining Youth Music |work=The New York Times |date=November 24, 1992 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> [[Cooper Union]]'s multimedia presentation \"Hiccup\" in 1993, Apple's 1995 \"Future Arts Panel\" with [[Peter Gabriel]] and [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] founder, [[John Perry Barlow]], George Washington University's Law School Summit [[Future of Music Coalition]] in 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.futureofmusic.org/newsletter/fmc-newsletter-60-september-6-2007 |title=FMC Newsletter No. 60 &#124; Future of Music Coalition |publisher=Futureofmusic.org |date=July 8, 2015 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> and New York University's \"NYU Panel Nelson Sullivan: Vlogging in the 80s\" in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2013/04/09/fales-hosts-a-panel-discussion-nelson-sullivan-vlogging-in-the-80s-april-25.html|title=NYU Fales Library Hosts A Panel Discussion Nelson Sullivan Vlogging in the 80s|publisher=Nyu.edu|accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> In 2013 she was featured in an exhibit entitled \"NYC 1993\", which was presented through New York City's [[New Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newmuseum.org/exhibitions/view/nyc-1993-experimental-jet-set-trash-and-no-star |title=NYC 1993: Experimental Jet Set, Trash and No Star |publisher=New Museum |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> Beyond the installation, her voice recording was played via pay phones throughout the New York area. In 2013, Lady Miss Kier was the featured voiceover artist in The Jazz Foundation of America's animated promo for the event \"A Great Night in Harlem.\"<ref>[http://jazzfoundation.org/Apollo2014] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140815003727/http://jazzfoundation.org/Apollo2014 |date=August 15, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Yn8-WjVkpFk |title=A Great Night in Harlem: Animated Promo |via=YouTube |date=April 25, 2013 |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==''Space Channel 5'' and lawsuit==\nIn 2003, Kirby sued video game company [[Sega]], claiming that the character of \"[[Space Channel 5#Characters|Ulala]]\" in its [[Dreamcast]] game ''[[Space Channel 5]]'' was an unauthorized use of her likeness.<ref name=lawsuit>{{cite web|url=http://www.ladykier.com/segacase.htm |title=Lady Kier VS Sega |publisher=Ladykier.com |accessdate=December 11, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061206003216/http://ladykier.com/segacase.htm |archivedate=December 6, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Kirby claimed that Sega offered to pay her {{USD|16,000}} to license her name, image and songs for the game, though she rejected its offer. Kirby alleged that the video game maker later used her resemblance anyway (including the name Ulala \u2013 referencing Kirby's signature phrase \"Ooh la la\" in her recorded and live performances), at which point she initiated the lawsuit. She ultimately lost the suit.<ref name=lawsuit2>{{cite court | litigants=Kirby v. Sega | court=Court of Appeal of California, 2nd District, Div. 8 | date=September 25, 2006 | accessdate=August 30, 2016 | url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=3191814113989354720&q=%2250+Cal.Rptr.3d+607&hl=en&as_sdt=2002 | }}</ref>\n\n==Political views and activism==\nLady Kier used her popularity as a platform to promote a variety of causes and is widely known not only as a singer, DJ, and fashion icon, but also as a social, environmental, and human rights activist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ocweekly.com/illustrated-homage-to-deee-lites-lady-miss-kier-7925215/|title=Illustrated Homage To Deee-Lite's Lady Miss Kier|date=February 24, 2017|work=OC Weekly|access-date=July 12, 2018}}</ref> She is a vocal advocate for LGBTQ rights and a longtime celebrated ally of the LGBTQ community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grownasslady.com/2014/05/27/style-icon-lady-miss-kier/|title=Style Icon: Lady Miss Kier \u00ab Grown Ass Lady|website=grownasslady.com|access-date=July 12, 2018}}</ref> As such, she is frequently invited to host, perform, MC, and DJ gay pride parades and associated events internationally.<ref>{{Citation|last=Mikey Sin|title=Mayor Rob Ford calls Lady Miss Kier (Deee-lite) at Pride Toronto|date=July 4, 2012|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pOOoB-COUsk|access-date=July 12, 2018}}</ref> She is staunchly pro-abortion rights and is a women's rights advocate, was featured in TV informercial promoting pro-abortion rights political action \"The Most Exciting Women in Music\" alongside [[Corina (singer)|Corina]], [[Juliet Cuming]], [[Kim Gordon]] ([[Sonic Youth]]), [[MC Lyte]], [[Kate Pierson]] ([[The B-52's]]), [[Crystal Waters]], [[Tina Weymouth]] ([[Talking Heads]], [[Tom Tom Club]]) in 1991.<ref>{{Citation|last=CheeseFoodProduct|title=The Most Exciting Women in Music|date=November 7, 2011|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qUMLLsQozMg|access-date=July 12, 2018}}</ref> In 1991, Lady Miss Kier was an award presenter at The Reebok Human Rights Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bkhonline.com/the-reebook-human-rights-awards/|title=The Reebok Human Rights Awards &#124; Black History|date=March 16, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nA strong supporter of environmental causes, her album \"Infinity Within\" was the first CD ever released using eco-pak packaging, cutting the amount of plastic used by half. A portion of the album's profits was pledged to Greenpeace and she was recognized for her efforts with an environmental media award from the World Wildlife Fund.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.studio-nibble.com/cd/index.php?title=Eco-Pak|title=Eco-Pak \u2013 cdHistory|website=studio-nibble.com|access-date=July 12, 2018}}</ref> As part of her environmental activism, she called attention to the issue of [[ozone depletion]] on the Deee-lite album ''Infinity Within'' with her song \"I Had a Dream I Was Falling Through a Hole in the Ozone Layer\"<ref>{{Citation|title=Deee-Lite \u2013 I Had a Dream I Was Falling Through a Hole in the Ozone Layer|url=https://genius.com/Deee-lite-i-had-a-dream-i-was-falling-through-a-hole-in-the-ozone-layer-lyrics|access-date=July 12, 2018}}</ref> and ''Vogue'' Magazine has highlighted her \"interest in supporting environmental causes\".<ref name=\"Vogue\" /> She is an anti-war activist and in 2010, she released a new version of the P-Funk track \"Bullet Proof\" with Ray Mang with lyrics calling attention to the perils of war and denouncing global militarization after the song was featured in 2005 during her world tour.<ref>{{Citation|last=WestSavannah|title=Ray Mang (featuring Lady Kier) \u2013 Bulletproof|date=February 2, 2010|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cZFxHc_Jwco|access-date=July 12, 2018}}</ref> She is a longtime leader in getting out the vote and encouraging Americans to register to vote. Her music video \"Vote Baby Vote\" was featured for MTV's \"Rock The Vote\" in 1992 and was highlighted by Rolling Stone Magazine as one of the top \"ten major moments in rock the vote history\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/pictures/10-major-moments-in-rock-the-vote-history-20160712/deee-lites-vote-baby-vote-1992-20160711|title=10 Major Moments in Rock the Vote History|last=Runtagh|first=Jordan|date=July 12, 2016|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=July 12, 2018}}</ref> During the 2016 U.S. Presidential election, she ultimately voted for [[Green Party of the United States|Green Party]] candidate [[Jill Stein]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Deeeeeelite/posts/10154530170449717 |title=Lady Miss Kier |publisher=Facebook }}{{Primary source inline|date=January 2020}}</ref> but was an outspoken and enthusiastic supporter of Bernie Sanders. To promote Bernie Sanders, she hosted an art exhibit at Hole Gallery in New York City and a fundraiser called \"Bernin' Up NYC\" to rally supporters get out the vote.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://gothamist.com/2016/04/01/bernie_sanders_bronx_rally.php#photo-14|title=Bernie in the Bronx: \"If We Win NY We Are Going To Make It To The White House!\"|work=Gothamist|access-date=July 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829111721/http://gothamist.com/2016/04/01/bernie_sanders_bronx_rally.php#photo-14|archive-date=August 29, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Official Website}}\n*[http://www.discogs.com/artist/Deee-Lite Deee-Lite Discography]\n*{{IMDb name|1398296}}\n\n{{Deee-Lite}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kier, Lady Miss}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American dance musicians]]\n[[Category:American female songwriters]]\n[[Category:American pop musicians]]\n[[Category:American house musicians]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:Club DJs]]\n[[Category:American female DJs]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Youngstown, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Fashion Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Singers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Deee-Lite members]]\n[[Category:American women in electronic music]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:American hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:American female hip hop musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Steven Menendez", "label": "safe", "comment": "Previous image did not show her face or persona well, this is a higher quality photo from same era.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lady_Miss_Kier"}
{"title_page": "Tughlakabad railway station", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name            = Tughlakabad\n| native_name     = \u0924\u0941\u0917\u093c\u0932\u0915\u093e\u092c\u093e\u0926\n| type            = [[Indian Railways|Indian Railway]]  Station\n| style           = Indian Railways\n| image           = Tughlakabad Railway Station.jpg\n| image_caption   = \n| address         = Tughlakabad, [[Delhi]]\n| country         = India\n| coordinates     = {{Coord|28.5035|N|77.2965|E|type:railwaystation_region:IN|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation     = {{convert|213.317|m|ft}}\n| line            = [[Kanpur-Delhi section|Agra-Delhi chord]]\n| other           = \n| structure       = Standard on ground\n| platform        = 2?\n| tracks          = \n| parking         = No\n| bicycle          = No\n| opened          = 1904\n| closed          = \n| rebuilt         = \n| electrified     = \n| ADA             = \n| code            = {{Indian railway code\n  | code = TKD\n  | division = Delhi\n  }}\n| owned           = [[Indian Railways]]\n| operator        = [[Northern Railway zone|Northern Railway]]\n| status           = Functioning\n| former          = \n| passengers      = \n| pass_year       = \n| pass_percent    = \n| pass_system     = \n| map_locator     = {{Location map|India Haryana|lat=28.5035|long=77.2965|width=300|caption=|label='''Tughlakabad''' railway station}}\n}}\n'''Tughlakabad railway station''' (station code:- '''TKD''') is on the [[Kanpur-Delhi section|Kanpur-Tundla-Agra-Delhi line]].  It is located in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Delhi]]. It is operated by [[Northern Railway Zone (India)|Northern Railway]], [[Delhi]] Division of [[Delhi]].\n\n==History==\nThe [[Kanpur-Delhi section|Agra-Delhi chord]] was opened in 1904.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-history3.html|title = IR History: Part III (1900-1947)| publisher= IRFCA| accessdate =7 July 2013 }}</ref> Some parts of it were relaid during the construction of New Delhi (inaugurated in 1927-28).<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/TopStories/A-fine-balance-of-luxury-and-care/Article1-723880.aspx | title = A fine balance of luxury and care | publisher = Hindusthan Times, 6 July 2013 | accessdate = 7 July 2013 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130602112944/http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/TopStories/A-fine-balance-of-luxury-and-care/Article1-723880.aspx | archivedate = 2 June 2013 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Passengers==\nTughlakabad railway station serves around 33,000 passengers every day.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://railenquiry.in/stationinfo/TKD/Tugalakabad|title = Tuglakabad (TKD)| publisher= Indian Rail Enquiry| accessdate =7 July 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Suburban railway==\nTughlakabad is part of the [[Delhi Suburban Railway]] and is served by [[Electrical multiple units|EMU]] trains.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.metrotrains.in/2012/01/delhi-suburban-railways.html |title = Delhi Suburban Railways  | publisher= Metro trains | accessdate =7 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Metro link==\n[[Tughlakabad metro station]] is about 1&nbsp;km from Tughlakabad railway station. It is on the [[Violet Line (Delhi Metro)|Violet Line]] of [[Delhi Metro]]. The line operates underground from Kashmere gate till Jangpura metro station. From there it is an elevated line till Raja Nahar Singh ([[Ballabhgarh]]) metro station. The Violet Line was opened up to Sarita Vihar in 2010 and up to Badarpur in 2011.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.indiaonlinepages.com/delhi/delhi-metro/voilet-line.html |title = Violet line Delhi Metro| publisher= Delhi Metro| accessdate =7 July 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Loco sheds==\nTughlakabad broad gauge diesel loco shed houses [[Indian locomotive class WDM-2|WDM-2]], [[WDM 3A]], WDM-3C, [[Indian locomotive class WDM-3D|WDM-3D]], [[Indian locomotive class WDP-1|WDP-1]], [[Indian locomotive class WDP-3A|WDP-3A]] and [[WDP-4B]]/[[WDP-4D]]. It has more than 150 locos.<ref name=sheds>{{cite web |url= http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-shed.html  |title= Sheds and workshops|publisher= IRFCA| accessdate = 10 July 2013 }}</ref>\n\nTughlakabad electric loco shed is a [[West Central Railway zone|West Central Railway]] shed located in Northern Railway territory.  It was a Western Railway shed till 2003. It was originally built to serve freight traffic on the busy Delhi-Mumbai route. It houses more than 250 locos of [[Indian locomotive class WAP-7|WAP-7]] and [[Indian locomotive class WAG-9|WAG-9]].<ref name=sheds/>\n\n==Yards and depots==\nTughlakabad marshalling yard is a mechanized hump yard with retarders.  It has an Inland Container depot with container freight station and also a domestic container terminal.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-yard.html |title= Freight Sheds and Mashalling Yards |publisher= IRFCA| accessdate = 10 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{external media\n| align=right\n| video1=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KvU48wIduSk Tamilnadu Express speeds through Tughlakabad]\n| video2=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cFlBNnaItFw Tughlakabad metro station]\n}}\n\n{{s-rail-start|noclear=yes}}\n{{s-rail|title=Indian Railways}}\n{{s-line|system=Indian Railways |previous=  Faridabad|next= Okhla|line= Northern Railway zone|branch= [[Kanpur-Delhi section|Agra-Delhi chord]]|rows1=1}}\n{{end}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in South Delhi district]]\n[[Category:Delhi railway division]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1904]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name            = Tughlakabad\n| type            = [[Indian Railways|Indian Railway]]  Station\n| style           = Indian Railways\n| image           = Tughlakabad Railway Station.jpg\n| image_caption   = \n| address         = Tughlakabad, [[Delhi]]\n| country         = India\n| coordinates     = {{Coord|28.5035|N|77.2965|E|type:railwaystation_region:IN|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation     = {{convert|213.317|m|ft}}\n| line            = [[Kanpur-Delhi section|Agra-Delhi chord]]\n| other           = \n| structure       = Standard on ground\n| platform        = 2?\n| tracks          = \n| parking         = No\n| bicycle          = No\n| opened          = 1904\n| closed          = \n| rebuilt         = \n| electrified     = \n| ADA             = \n| code            = {{Indian railway code\n  | code = TKD\n  | division = Delhi\n  }}\n| owned           = [[Indian Railways]]\n| operator        = [[Northern Railway zone|Northern Railway]]\n| status           = Functioning\n| former          = \n| passengers      = \n| pass_year       = \n| pass_percent    = \n| pass_system     = \n| map_locator     = {{Location map|India Haryana|lat=28.5035|long=77.2965|width=300|caption=|label='''Tughlakabad''' railway station}}\n}}\n'''Tughlakabad railway station''' (station code:- '''TKD''') is on the [[Kanpur-Delhi section|Kanpur-Tundla-Agra-Delhi line]].  It is located in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Delhi]]. It is operated by [[Northern Railway Zone (India)|Northern Railway]], [[Delhi]] Division of [[Delhi]].\n\n==History==\nThe [[Kanpur-Delhi section|Agra-Delhi chord]] was opened in 1904.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-history3.html|title = IR History: Part III (1900-1947)| publisher= IRFCA| accessdate =7 July 2013 }}</ref> Some parts of it were relaid during the construction of New Delhi (inaugurated in 1927-28).<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/TopStories/A-fine-balance-of-luxury-and-care/Article1-723880.aspx | title = A fine balance of luxury and care | publisher = Hindusthan Times, 6 July 2013 | accessdate = 7 July 2013 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130602112944/http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/TopStories/A-fine-balance-of-luxury-and-care/Article1-723880.aspx | archivedate = 2 June 2013 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Passengers==\nTughlakabad railway station serves around 33,000 passengers every day.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://railenquiry.in/stationinfo/TKD/Tugalakabad|title = Tuglakabad (TKD)| publisher= Indian Rail Enquiry| accessdate =7 July 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Suburban railway==\nTughlakabad is part of the [[Delhi Suburban Railway]] and is served by [[Electrical multiple units|EMU]] trains.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.metrotrains.in/2012/01/delhi-suburban-railways.html |title = Delhi Suburban Railways  | publisher= Metro trains | accessdate =7 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Metro link==\n[[Tughlakabad metro station]] is about 1&nbsp;km from Tughlakabad railway station. It is on the [[Violet Line (Delhi Metro)|Violet Line]] of [[Delhi Metro]]. The line operates underground from Kashmere gate till Jangpura metro station. From there it is an elevated line till Raja Nahar Singh ([[Ballabhgarh]]) metro station. The Violet Line was opened up to Sarita Vihar in 2010 and up to Badarpur in 2011.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.indiaonlinepages.com/delhi/delhi-metro/voilet-line.html |title = Violet line Delhi Metro| publisher= Delhi Metro| accessdate =7 July 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Loco sheds==\nTughlakabad broad gauge diesel loco shed houses [[Indian locomotive class WDM-2|WDM-2]], [[WDM 3A]], WDM-3C, [[Indian locomotive class WDM-3D|WDM-3D]], [[Indian locomotive class WDP-1|WDP-1]], [[Indian locomotive class WDP-3A|WDP-3A]] and [[WDP-4B]]/[[WDP-4D]]. It has more than 150 locos.<ref name=sheds>{{cite web |url= http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-shed.html  |title= Sheds and workshops|publisher= IRFCA| accessdate = 10 July 2013 }}</ref>\n\nTughlakabad electric loco shed is a [[West Central Railway zone|West Central Railway]] shed located in Northern Railway territory.  It was a Western Railway shed till 2003. It was originally built to serve freight traffic on the busy Delhi-Mumbai route. It houses more than 250 locos of [[Indian locomotive class WAP-7|WAP-7]] and [[Indian locomotive class WAG-9|WAG-9]].<ref name=sheds/>\n\n==Yards and depots==\nTughlakabad marshalling yard is a mechanized hump yard with retarders.  It has an Inland Container depot with container freight station and also a domestic container terminal.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-yard.html |title= Freight Sheds and Mashalling Yards |publisher= IRFCA| accessdate = 10 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{external media\n| align=right\n| video1=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KvU48wIduSk Tamilnadu Express speeds through Tughlakabad]\n| video2=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cFlBNnaItFw Tughlakabad metro station]\n}}\n\n{{s-rail-start|noclear=yes}}\n{{s-rail|title=Indian Railways}}\n{{s-line|system=Indian Railways |previous=  Faridabad|next= Okhla|line= Northern Railway zone|branch= [[Kanpur-Delhi section|Agra-Delhi chord]]|rows1=1}}\n{{end}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in South Delhi district]]\n[[Category:Delhi railway division]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1904]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4041:2e97:df23::2109:e501", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tughlakabad_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "Itarsi Junction railway station", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{third-party|date=January 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2017}}\n}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name            = Itarsi Junction\n| native_name     = \u0907\u091f\u093e\u0930\u0938\u0940 \u091c\u0902\u0915\u094d\u0936\u0928\n| native_name_lang= \n| type            = [[Regional rail]], [[Light rail]] & [[Commuter rail]]\n| style           = Indian railway\n| image           = File:Itarsi junction stone.jpg\n| caption         = Itarsi junction board\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord = {{coord|22.6085438|N|77.7668953|E}}   <!-- Map center -->\n| float = center\n| zoom = 14\n| width = 290 <!-- width and height of the frame. numeric input - do not add px -->\n| height = 200\n| caption = {{center|Locations of Itarsi Jn}}\n}}\n| address         = [[Itarsi]], [[Madhya Pradesh]]\n| country         = India\n| coordinates     = {{Coord|22.608|77.767|type:railwaystation_region:IN|format=dms|display=inline}}\n| elevation       = {{convert|329.400|m|ft}}\n| line            = [[Howrah-Allahabad-Mumbai line]]<br/>[[Delhi-Chennai line]] \n| other           = \n| platform        = 8\n| tracks          = 11\n| code            = {{Indian railway code\n  | code = ET\n  | zone = [[West Central Railways]]\n  | division = [[Bhopal railway division]]\n  }}\n| owned           = [[Indian Railways]]\n| status          = Functioning\n| map_locator     = {{Location map|India#India Madhya Pradesh#India|lat=22.608|long=77.767|width=300|caption= Location in Madhya Pradesh|label= '''Itarsi''' railway station}}\n}}\n{{Delhi\u2013Chennai line|collapse=y}}\n{{Howrah-Allahabad-Mumbai line|collapse=y}}\n'''Itarsi Junction''' (station code: ET) is a railway station in [[Hoshangabad|Hoshangabad District]] in [[Madhya Pradesh]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://indiarailinfo.com/station/map/itarsi-junction-et/13#st|title=Itarsi Junction railway station|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/indian-railway/itarsi-jn-et-station|title=ITARSI JN (ET) Railway Station|last=|first=|date=|website=[[NDTV|New Delhi Television Limited (NDTV)]] - Privately owned national television network|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 Feb 2019}}</ref> from which more than 385 trains pass every day. It is the 8th busiest railway junction in India.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}} It falls under the [[West Central Railway]] zone of [[Indian Railways]] network. It is located {{convert|18|km}} away from [[Hoshangabad]] by train, and by road it is 20 kilometers. Trains from Central Railway undergo engine changes here i.e. electric engines of WAP/WAM/WAG class are changed to diesel engines of WDP/WDM/WDG class and vice versa. These changes happen for trains which pass through Jabalpur-Katni-Satna railway line and sometimes for trains which pass through Bhopal.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gofoodieonline.com/Location/order-food-in-train-at-Itarsi-Junction|title=Overview of Itarsi Railway Station \u2013 ET|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 Feb 2019}}</ref> In 2015 the signal control system was gutted in a fire incident resulting in hundreds of trains being cancelled for over 30 days till normality was restored.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.iricen.gov.in/iricen/ipwe_seminar/2016/5.pdf|title=ITARSI RRI fire - NOT AN ORDINARY DISRUPTION|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 Feb 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Structure and location==\nThe railway station of [[Itarsi]] consists of eight platforms. The platforms are well furnished to meet up with all the passenger needs and demands.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Connectivity==\n[[Itarsi|Itarsi Junction]] Railway station is very well connected with rail routes from all four sides. Thus there are trains for almost all the Indian destinations.\n\nStatus of arrival and departure of trains at Itarsi junction can be viewed via live station through National Train Enquiry System.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://enquiry.indianrail.gov.in/xyzabc/LiveStation?stnCode=ET&toStnCode=&withinHrs=8&trainType=ALL&scrnSize=&langFile=props.en-us|title=Indian Railways National Train Enquiry System|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Lines==\nThe tracks on the junction are such that they provide a vast connection to all the four directions. To the north lies the important capital city of [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[Bhopal Junction|Bhopal]]. To the east lies another important railway junction [[Jabalpur]]. To the southwest lies [[Khandwa]] and [[Bhusawal]], and to the southeast lies [[Amla, Madhya Pradesh|Amla Jn.]], [[Betul, Madhya Pradesh|Betul]] and [[Nagpur]]. The station always holds heavy over-traffic as the trains on the [[Howrah\u2013Allahabad\u2013Mumbai line]] and [[Jhansi]] \u2013 [[Bhopal Junction|Bhopal Jn.]] \u2013 [[Nagpur]] routes cross at Itarsi.\n\n== 2015 Fire incident ==\nOn 17 June 2015, there was a fire incident on Itarsi junction involving signal control system resulting in extensive damage to [[Interlocking|route relay interlocking]] system (RRI). This resulted in trains being stranded at the station other trains heading towards station being cancelled or diverted. Initially the extent of damage was considered small, but subsequent inspection post fire control found RRI in ashes, beyond repair. A deadline was set to commission new RRI in 35 days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/specials/india-file/reconnecting/article7699050.ece|title=The Railways' reconstruction of the gutted signalling system of Itarsi station|last=|first=|date=28 Sep 2015|work=[[The Hindu Business Line]]|access-date=22 Feb 2019}}</ref> 78 trains were cancelled and 23 diverted by second day alone.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/itarsi-station-fire-78-trains-cancelled-23-diverted-773056|title=Itarsi Station Fire: 78 Trains Cancelled, 23 Diverted|last=|first=|date=18 June 2015|work=[[NDTV]]|access-date=22 Feb 2019}}</ref> Thirty four days disruption resulted in cancellation of 2,044 trains, diversion of 249 trains and short termination of 17 trains. The new RRI installation was completed on 21 July at a cost of Rs. 19.64 cr. Complete normalcy was restored by 26 July 2015.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/new-signalling-control-room-at-itarsi-becomes-operational/articleshow/48164503.cms|title=New signalling control room at Itarsi becomes operational|last=|first=|date=21 July 2015|work=[[The Economic Times]]|access-date=22 Feb 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bhopal Junction]]\n* [[Katni Junction]]\n* [[Hoshangabad]]\n* [[Ghoradongri Railway Station]]\n* [[Bhopal Habibganj]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wcr.indianrailways.gov.in/testwcr.jsp?DIVISION_ID=1&STATION_ID=Itarsi Itarsi Junction railway station in pictures]\n* [https://www.openstreetmap.org/node/718916832#map=16/22.6086/77.7671 Itarsi Junction on OpenStreetMap]\n\n{{commons category}}\n{{Railway stations in Madhya Pradesh}}\n\n[[Category:Railway junction stations in Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Bhopal railway division]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Hoshangabad district]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{third-party|date=January 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2017}}\n}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name            = Itarsi Junction\n| native_name     = \n| native_name_lang= \n| type            = [[Regional rail]], [[Light rail]] & [[Commuter rail]]\n| style           = Indian railway\n| image           = File:Itarsi junction stone.jpg\n| caption         = Itarsi junction board\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord = {{coord|22.6085438|N|77.7668953|E}}   <!-- Map center -->\n| float = center\n| zoom = 14\n| width = 290 <!-- width and height of the frame. numeric input - do not add px -->\n| height = 200\n| caption = {{center|Locations of Itarsi Jn}}\n}}\n| address         = [[Itarsi]], [[Madhya Pradesh]]\n| country         = India\n| coordinates     = {{Coord|22.608|77.767|type:railwaystation_region:IN|format=dms|display=inline}}\n| elevation       = {{convert|329.400|m|ft}}\n| line            = [[Howrah-Allahabad-Mumbai line]]<br/>[[Delhi-Chennai line]] \n| other           = \n| platform        = 8\n| tracks          = 11\n| code            = {{Indian railway code\n  | code = ET\n  | zone = [[West Central Railways]]\n  | division = [[Bhopal railway division]]\n  }}\n| owned           = [[Indian Railways]]\n| status          = Functioning\n| map_locator     = {{Location map|India#India Madhya Pradesh#India|lat=22.608|long=77.767|width=300|caption= Location in Madhya Pradesh|label= '''Itarsi''' railway station}}\n}}\n{{Delhi\u2013Chennai line|collapse=y}}\n{{Howrah-Allahabad-Mumbai line|collapse=y}}\n'''Itarsi Junction''' (station code: ET) is a railway station in [[Hoshangabad|Hoshangabad District]] in [[Madhya Pradesh]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://indiarailinfo.com/station/map/itarsi-junction-et/13#st|title=Itarsi Junction railway station|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/indian-railway/itarsi-jn-et-station|title=ITARSI JN (ET) Railway Station|last=|first=|date=|website=[[NDTV|New Delhi Television Limited (NDTV)]] - Privately owned national television network|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 Feb 2019}}</ref> from which more than 385 trains pass every day. It is the 8th busiest railway junction in India.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}} It falls under the [[West Central Railway]] zone of [[Indian Railways]] network. It is located {{convert|18|km}} away from [[Hoshangabad]] by train, and by road it is 20 kilometers. Trains from Central Railway undergo engine changes here i.e. electric engines of WAP/WAM/WAG class are changed to diesel engines of WDP/WDM/WDG class and vice versa. These changes happen for trains which pass through Jabalpur-Katni-Satna railway line and sometimes for trains which pass through Bhopal.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gofoodieonline.com/Location/order-food-in-train-at-Itarsi-Junction|title=Overview of Itarsi Railway Station \u2013 ET|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 Feb 2019}}</ref> In 2015 the signal control system was gutted in a fire incident resulting in hundreds of trains being cancelled for over 30 days till normality was restored.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.iricen.gov.in/iricen/ipwe_seminar/2016/5.pdf|title=ITARSI RRI fire - NOT AN ORDINARY DISRUPTION|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 Feb 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Structure and location==\nThe railway station of [[Itarsi]] consists of eight platforms. The platforms are well furnished to meet up with all the passenger needs and demands.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Connectivity==\n[[Itarsi|Itarsi Junction]] Railway station is very well connected with rail routes from all four sides. Thus there are trains for almost all the Indian destinations.\n\nStatus of arrival and departure of trains at Itarsi junction can be viewed via live station through National Train Enquiry System.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://enquiry.indianrail.gov.in/xyzabc/LiveStation?stnCode=ET&toStnCode=&withinHrs=8&trainType=ALL&scrnSize=&langFile=props.en-us|title=Indian Railways National Train Enquiry System|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Lines==\nThe tracks on the junction are such that they provide a vast connection to all the four directions. To the north lies the important capital city of [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[Bhopal Junction|Bhopal]]. To the east lies another important railway junction [[Jabalpur]]. To the southwest lies [[Khandwa]] and [[Bhusawal]], and to the southeast lies [[Amla, Madhya Pradesh|Amla Jn.]], [[Betul, Madhya Pradesh|Betul]] and [[Nagpur]]. The station always holds heavy over-traffic as the trains on the [[Howrah\u2013Allahabad\u2013Mumbai line]] and [[Jhansi]] \u2013 [[Bhopal Junction|Bhopal Jn.]] \u2013 [[Nagpur]] routes cross at Itarsi.\n\n== 2015 Fire incident ==\nOn 17 June 2015, there was a fire incident on Itarsi junction involving signal control system resulting in extensive damage to [[Interlocking|route relay interlocking]] system (RRI). This resulted in trains being stranded at the station other trains heading towards station being cancelled or diverted. Initially the extent of damage was considered small, but subsequent inspection post fire control found RRI in ashes, beyond repair. A deadline was set to commission new RRI in 35 days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/specials/india-file/reconnecting/article7699050.ece|title=The Railways' reconstruction of the gutted signalling system of Itarsi station|last=|first=|date=28 Sep 2015|work=[[The Hindu Business Line]]|access-date=22 Feb 2019}}</ref> 78 trains were cancelled and 23 diverted by second day alone.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/itarsi-station-fire-78-trains-cancelled-23-diverted-773056|title=Itarsi Station Fire: 78 Trains Cancelled, 23 Diverted|last=|first=|date=18 June 2015|work=[[NDTV]]|access-date=22 Feb 2019}}</ref> Thirty four days disruption resulted in cancellation of 2,044 trains, diversion of 249 trains and short termination of 17 trains. The new RRI installation was completed on 21 July at a cost of Rs. 19.64 cr. Complete normalcy was restored by 26 July 2015.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/new-signalling-control-room-at-itarsi-becomes-operational/articleshow/48164503.cms|title=New signalling control room at Itarsi becomes operational|last=|first=|date=21 July 2015|work=[[The Economic Times]]|access-date=22 Feb 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bhopal Junction]]\n* [[Katni Junction]]\n* [[Hoshangabad]]\n* [[Ghoradongri Railway Station]]\n* [[Bhopal Habibganj]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wcr.indianrailways.gov.in/testwcr.jsp?DIVISION_ID=1&STATION_ID=Itarsi Itarsi Junction railway station in pictures]\n* [https://www.openstreetmap.org/node/718916832#map=16/22.6086/77.7671 Itarsi Junction on OpenStreetMap]\n\n{{commons category}}\n{{Railway stations in Madhya Pradesh}}\n\n[[Category:Railway junction stations in Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Bhopal railway division]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Hoshangabad district]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4041:2e97:df23::2109:e501", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Itarsi_Junction_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "Intercontinental Cup (football)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Intercontinental Cup (disambiguation){{!}}Intercontinental Cup}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox football tournament\n| name                 = Intercontinental Cup <br>{{small|European/South American Cup}} <br> {{small|Toyota Cup}}\n| image                = Intercontinental cup.png\n| imagesize            = 100px\n| caption              = The trophy given to champions\n| organiser            = [[UEFA]]  [[CONMEBOL]]\n| founded              = [[1960 Intercontinental Cup|1960]]\n| abolished            = [[2004 Intercontinental Cup|2004]]\n| region               = Europe <br> South America\n| number of teams      = 2\n| related comps        = [[UEFA Champions League]]<br> [[Copa Libertadores]]\n| domestic cup         = \n| confed cup           = \n| current champions    = {{flagicon|POR}} [[FC Porto|Porto]] <br> (2nd title)\n| most successful club = \n{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Boca Juniors]]<br>{{flagicon|ITA}} [[A.C. Milan|Milan]]<br>{{flagicon|URU}} [[Club Nacional de Football|Nacional]]<br>{{flagicon|URU}} [[Pe\u00f1arol]]<br>{{flagicon|ESP}} [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]<br>(3 titles each)\n}}\n\nThe '''Intercontinental Cup''', also known as '''European/South American Cup''', and also '''Toyota Cup''' from 1980 to 2004 for commercial reasons by agreement with the [[Toyota|automaker]], was an international [[association football|football]] competition endorsed by the [[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] (UEFA) and the [[CONMEBOL|Confederaci\u00f3n Sudamericana de F\u00fatbol]] (CONMEBOL),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/printoutfiles/competitions/ucl/2010/e/e_01_md.pdf|title=Legend \u2013 UEFA club competition|work=Union des Associations Europ\u00e9ennes de Football|format=PDF|page=99|year=2009|accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|language=Spanish|url=http://www.conmebol.com/books/Repasando%20la%20Historia/Repasando%20la%20Historia.html|title=Competencias oficiales de la CONMEBOL|work=Confederaci\u00f3n Sudamericana de F\u00fatbol|pages=99; 107|year=2011|accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref><ref>- The winners of UEFA Champions League undertake to part in the following competitions: \na) The UEFA Super cup, which is held at the start of each new season.\nb) Intercontinental competitions arranged by UEFA and other confederations.\n\u2013 Clubs are not authorised to represent UEFA or the UEFA Champions\nLeague without UEFA's prior written approval. cfr. {{cite news|url=https://kassiesa.net/uefafiles/2003-uefa-cl-rules.pdf|title=We care about football \u2013 Regulation of the UEFA Champions League 2003/04|publisher=Union of European Football Associations|format=PDF|pages=2}}</ref> contested between representative clubs from these confederations (representatives of most developed continents in the football world), usually the winners of the [[UEFA Champions League]] and the South American [[Copa Libertadores]]. All editions were official competitions of UEFA and CONMEBOL<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=http://conmebol.com/es/19082015-1742/las-competiciones-oficiales-de-la-conmebol|title=Las competiciones oficiales de la CONMEBOL|last=Official competitions are those recognized as valid by an organization and not only organized by it, in fact Conmebol includes in its list of official competitions the Club World Cup that is fully organized by FIFA.|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|publisher=CONMEBOL}}</ref><ref name=\"uefa.com2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/teamsandplayers/teams/club=50051/profile/index.html|title=Real Madrid CF|publisher=UEFA}}</ref> and indirectly also of [[FIFA]].<ref name=\":F1542\">For FIFA statute, official competitions are those for representative teams organized by FIFA or any confederation. Representative teams are usually national teams but also club teams that represent a confederation in the interconfederal competitions or a member association in a continental competition cfr. {{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/the-fifa-statutes-in-force-as-of-27-april-2016-2782908.pdf?cloudid=vga5sv1yxeayptzrdudx|title=FIFA Statutes, April 2016 edition|page=5|format=PDF}} cfr. {{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/statistical-kit-fifa-club-world-cup-uae-2018.pdf?cloudid=mkbo3nwk4btahl9gwtwl|title=FIFA Club World Cup UAE 2018: Statistical-kit|date=10 December 2018|page=13|format=PDF}} cfr. {{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/MultimediaFiles/Download/Regulations/uefaorg/Regulations/02/55/82/79/2558279_DOWNLOAD.pdf|title=2018/19 UEFA Champions League regulations|page=10|format=PDF}}</ref><ref name=\":F153\">In accordance with the regulations integrated in the FIFA Statute, official competitions for club teams can be defined as those organized under the auspices of FIFA, confederations and member associations, or authorized by them, excluding friendly matches and test matches; say the confederal and interconfederal cups (arranged by FIFA or confederations), the championships and the national cups (arranged by member associations). cfr. {{cite web|url=https://img.fifa.com/image/upload/datdz0pms85gbnqy4j3k.pdf|title=LAWS OF THE GAME 2015/16|language=en|format=PDF|p=18}} cfr. {{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/mm/document/affederation/administration/02/70/95/52/regulationsonthestatusandtransferofplayersjune2016_e_neutral.pdf|title=REGULATIONS on the Status and Transfer of Players 2016|format=PDF|p=5.}} cfr. {{cite web|url=https://img.fifa.com/image/upload/dcu3yijbaqnz9op1y1jf.pdf|title=FIFA Governance Regulations (FGR) 2016|editor=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association|format=PDF|pp=6\u20137, 9\u201311}} cfr. {{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/regulations-governing-international-matches-2325685.pdf?cloudid=pywuivvlfl5aqvhsw2i7|title=Regulations Governing International Matches|format=PDF|p=15, 25}} cfr. {{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/the-fifa-statutes-in-force-as-of-27-april-2016-2782908.pdf?cloudid=vga5sv1yxeayptzrdudx|title=FIFA Statutes, April 2016 edition|format=PDF|pp=5, 19\u201321, 33\u201335, 37, 44, 74}} cfr. {{cite web|url=http://www.publico.pt/noticia/fifa-ignora-taca-latina-do-benfica-fc-porto-e-o-clube-portugues-com-mais-titulos-1495851|title=FIFA ignora Ta\u00e7a Latina do Benfica, FC Porto \u00e9 o clube portugu\u00eas com mais t\u00edtulos|date=25 May 2011|language=pt|access-date=18 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150616073533/http://www.publico.pt/noticia/fifa-ignora-taca-latina-do-benfica-fc-porto-e-o-clube-portugues-com-mais-titulos-1495851|archive-date=16 June 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Santiago Garc\u00eda|language=es|url=http://hemeroteca.lavanguardia.com/preview/1960/07/03/pagina-34/32732189/pdf.html|title=Los campeones de las Copas de Europa y Sudam\u00e9rica, Real Madrid y Pe\u00f1arol, disputar\u00e1n el primer partido de la final de la Copa del Mundo de clubs|editor=La Vanguardia|p=34|format=PDF|date=3 July 1960}}</ref><ref>Until 1955 FIFA limited itself to authorizing the creation of international competitions for clubs only if they were organized by at least two member associations. From 1955 he assigned the confederations the exclusive right to organize competitions deemed official. cfr. {{cite web|url=https://kassiesa.net/uefa/files/2004-uefa-50-years-european-cup.pdf|title=50 years of the European Cup|author=Union des Associations Europ\u00e9ennes de Football|date=October 2004|format=PDF|pp=7-9}}</ref> It was succeeded by the [[FIFA Club World Cup]].\n\nFrom its formation in 1960 to 1979, the competition was contested over a two legged tie, with a playoff if necessary until 1968, and [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]]s later. During the 1970s, European participation in the Intercontinental Cup became a running question due to controversial events in the [[1969 Intercontinental Cup|1969 final]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/history/season=1969/intro.html|title=1969: Milan prevail in tough contest|publisher=Union des Associations Europ\u00e9ennes de Football|date=22 October 1969|accessdate=21 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226061327/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/history/season%3D1969/intro.html|archivedate=26 December 2015}}</ref> and some European Champions Club' winner teams withdrew.<ref name=\"Risolo\">Risolo, Don (2010). [https://books.google.com/books?id=sEh7A0arS8kC&pg=PA109&dq=intercontinental+cup+-+liverpool+refused+to+play&hl=en&sa=X&ei=CEZOT4fKO6Kt0QWSirieBQ&ved=0CD4Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=intercontinental%20cup%20-%20liverpool%20refused%20to%20play&f=false Soccer Stories: Anecdotes, Oddities, Lore, and Amazing Feats] p.109. U of Nebraska Press. Retrieved 29 February 2012.</ref> From 1980 until 2004, the competition was contested over a single match held in Japan and sponsored by [[multinational corporation|multinational]] [[automotive industry|automaker]] [[Toyota]], which offered a secondary trophy, the Toyota Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/fifafacts/mencompcwc/01/15/71/66/fcwc2012_kit.pdf|title=FIFA Club World Cup 2012 \u2013 Statistical Kit|page=9|work=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association|format=PDF|date=6 November 2012|accessdate=21 November 2012}}</ref> From 1980 the logistics organisation passed to the Japan Football Association<ref>{{cite news||language=pt|url=https://pt.uefa.com/insideuefa/about-uefa/history/news/newsid=1587395.html?redirectFromOrg=true|title=Rede do futebol mundial|author=Union of European Football Associations}}</ref> but the competitions was always under the aegis of UEFA and CONMEBOL.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"uefa.com2\" />\n\nAll the winning teams were regarded by worldwide mass media and football's community, FIFA included (as News Center productions and not catalogued on the FIFA website as official entity documents),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/about-fifa/who-we-are/official-documents/|title=OFFICIAL DOCUMENTS|publisher=FIFA.COM}}</ref> ''de facto'' as \"[[#International participation|world champions]]\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=107/edition=4735/news/newsid=101662.html|title=We are the champions|date=1 December 2005|accessdate=21 November 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430044235/http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament%3D107/edition%3D4735/news/newsid%3D101662.html|archivedate=30 April 2011|url-status=dead|publisher=FIFA.COM}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2431719.html|title=Ronaldo treble fires Madrid to Club World Cup glory|work=[[Union des Associations Europ\u00e9ennes de Football]]author=Joe Walker |date=18 December 2016|accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=132237.html|title=Maldini wants world title|work=Union des Associations Europ\u00e9ennes de Football|date=10 December 2003|accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/Document/AF-Magazine/FIFAWeekly/02/74/62/99/50_EN_Weekly_Lowres_50_EN_Neutral.PDF|title=Japan Aiming High|pages=8\u20139|work=The FIFA Weekly|issue=50|editor=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association|format=PDF|date=18 December 2015|accessdate=30 January 2017|oclc=862248672}}</ref> until 2017 when FIFA Council officially (''[[de jure]]'') recognised all of them as club world champions with the same status to the [[FIFA Club World Cup]] winners, then as official<ref name=\":F15232\">\"Official (''plural'' officials), from the Latin '' offici\u0101lis.'' 1. The official word is also used to refer to what is recognized or derives from an authority. cfr. {{cite web|url=https://www.dictionary.com/browse/official|title=Official, definition|author=dictionary.com}} 2. Approved by the government or someone in power. cfr. {{cite web|url=https://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/english-spanish/official|title=official|author=dictionary.cambridge.org}} It is synonymous with legal, legitimate, approved. cfr. {{cite web|url=https://www.thesaurus.com/browse/official|title=Synonyms for official|author=thesaurus.com}}</ref><ref name=\":F15423\">For FIFA statute, official competitions are those for representative teams organized by FIFA or any confederation. Representative teams are usually national teams but also club teams that represent a confederation in the interconfederal competitions or a member association in a continental competition cfr. {{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/the-fifa-statutes-in-force-as-of-27-april-2016-2782908.pdf?cloudid=vga5sv1yxeayptzrdudx|title=FIFA Statutes, April 2016 edition|page=5|format=PDF}} cfr. {{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/statistical-kit-fifa-club-world-cup-uae-2018.pdf?cloudid=mkbo3nwk4btahl9gwtwl|title=FIFA Club World Cup UAE 2018: Statistical-kit|date=10 December 2018|page=13|format=PDF}} cfr. {{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/MultimediaFiles/Download/Regulations/uefaorg/Regulations/02/55/82/79/2558279_DOWNLOAD.pdf|title=2018/19 UEFA Champions League regulations|page=10|format=PDF}}</ref> \"[[#International participation|world champions]]\" FIFA.<ref name=\":F1542332\">\u201cWhile it does not promote the statistical unification of tournaments, that is, has not absorbed to the Intercontinental Cup (merged with FIFA Club World Cup in 2005), FIFA is the only organization with worldwide jurisdiction over continental confederations and, then, the only one that can confer a title on that level, ergo the title assigned by FIFA with Official Document to the winners of the Intercontinental Cup is legally a FIFA world title.\"  cfr. {{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/the-fifa-statutes-in-force-as-of-27-april-2016-2782908.pdf?cloudid=vga5sv1yxeayptzrdudx|title=FIFA Statutes, April 2016 edition|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=19|format=PDF|access-date=}} cfr.</ref><ref name=\"kit2018\">{{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/statistical-kit-fifa-club-world-cup-uae-2018.pdf?cloudid=mkbo3nwk4btahl9gwtwl|title=FIFA Club World Cup UAE 2018: Statistical-kit|date=10 December 2018|pages=6, 9, 13.|format=PDF}}</ref><ref name=\"kit2017\">{{cite web|url=http://resources.fifa.com/mm/document/fifafacts/mencompcwc/02/67/91/87/statskit_fcwc2017_event_neutral.pdf|title=FIFA Club World Cup UAE 2017: Statistical Kit|pages=15, 40, 41, 42|format=PDF}}</ref><ref name=\"FIFA20173\">{{cite press release|date=27 October 2017|title=FIFA Council approves key organisational elements of the FIFA World Cup|url=https://www.fifa.com/about-fifa/news/y=2017/m=10/news=fifa-council-approves-key-organisational-elements-of-the-fifa-world-cu-2917722.html|publisher=FIFA|accessdate=27 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/fifa-acepta-propuesta-de-conembol-de-reconocer-titulos-de-copa-intercontinental-como-mundiales-de|title=FIFA acepta propuesta de CONMEBOL de reconocer t\u00edtulos de copa intercontinental como mundiales de clubes|date=29 October 2017|publisher=conmebol.com|language=Spanish}}</ref> The first winner of the cup was Spanish side [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]], defeating Uruguayan side [[Pe\u00f1arol]] in [[1960 Intercontinental Cup|1960]]. The last winner was Portuguese side [[FC Porto|Porto]], defeating Colombian side [[Once Caldas]] in a [[penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] in [[2004 Intercontinental Cup|2004]]. The competition ended in 2004 and it merged with the [[FIFA Club World Cup]] in 2005.<ref name=\"FIFA Activity Report 20053\" />\n\n==History==\n\n===Beginnings===\nAccording to Brazilian newspaper ''Tribuna de Imprensa'', the idea for the Intercontinental Cup rose in 1958 in a conversation between the then president of the Brazilian FA [[Jo\u00e3o Havelange]] and French journalist [[Jacques Goddet]].<ref>[http://memoria.bn.br/DocReader/docreader.aspx?bib=154083_01&pasta=ano%20195&pesq=cetro%20mundial Tribuna de Imprensa, ed. 2675, page. 8, of 23/10/1958. In Portuguese.]</ref> The first mention of the creation of the Intercontinental and [[Copa Libertadores|Libertadores]] Cups was published by Brazilian and Spanish newspapers on 9 October 1958, referring to Havelange's announcement of the project to create such competitions, which he uttered during a UEFA meeting he attended as an invitee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1958/07/25/pagina-4/637161/pdf.html?search=|title=Edici\u00f3n del $dateTool.format('EEEE d MMMM yyyy', $document.date), P\u00e1gina $document.page - Hemeroteca |website=hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hemeroteca.abc.es/nav/Navigate.exe/hemeroteca/madrid/abc/1958/10/09/058.html|title=ABC (Madrid) \u2013 09/10/1958, p. 58 \u2013 ABC.es Hemeroteca|website=ABC|location=Spain}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=0qX8s2k1IRwC&dat=19581009&printsec=frontpage&hl=pt-BR|title=Jornal do Brasil \u2013 Pesquisa de arquivos de not\u00edcias Google|publisher=Google News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://acervo.estadao.com.br/pagina/#!/19581009-25595-nac-0019-999-19-not/busca/Mundial+Clubes|title=O Estado de S. Paulo \u2013 Acervo Estad\u00e3o}}</ref> Prior to this announcement, the reigning European champions [[Real Madrid C.F.]] had already played two intercontinental club competitions, the 1956 [[Peque\u00f1a Copa del Mundo de Clubes]] and the 1957 [[Tournoi de Paris]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leyendablanca.galeon.com|title=Real Madrid, la leyenda blanca|website=leyendablanca.galeon.com}}</ref> According to a French video record of the highlights of the latter match, between [[Real Madrid C.F.]] and [[CR Vasco da Gama]], this was the first match ever dubbed as \"the best team of Europe vs. the best team of South America\".<ref name=\"casaca.com.br\">{{cite web|url=http://www.casaca.com.br/home/2012/06/14/ha-55-anos-o-vasco-conquistava-o-i-torneio-de-paris/.|title=CR Vasco da Gama's supporters' site \"Casaca\": \"H\u00e1 55 anos o Vasco conquistava o I Torneio de Paris\".}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/futebol/times/vasco/noticia/2012/06/dario-lembra-vitoria-do-vasco-sobre-real-em-1957-nao-ha-clube-igual.html|title=Dario lembra vit\u00f3ria do Vasco sobre Real, em 1957: \u2018N\u00e3o h\u00e1 clube igual\u2019}}</ref> It was described as \"being like a club world cup match\" by the Brazilian press,<ref>[http://memoria.bn.br/DocReader/docreader.aspx?bib=112518_02&pasta=ano%20195&pesq=mundial%20de%20clubes ''Jornal dos Sports'', Rio de Janeiro newspaper, ed. 8526, 18 June 1957, page 8, on Vasco da Gama's victory over Real Madrid at the 1957 Tournoi de Paris.]</ref><ref>[http://memoria.bn.br/DocReader/DocReader.aspx?bib=154083_01&PagFis=122&Pesq=Real%20Madri  ''Tribuna da Imprensa'', Rio de Janeiro newspaper, 14 June 1957, ed. 2264, on the Vasco da Gama Vs. Real Madrid CF match for the 1957 Tournoi de Paris, citing Real Madrid as current European Champions and Vasco da Gama as the current Rio de Janeiro champions.]</ref> as was a June 1959 friendly between Real Madrid and [[Torneio Rio \u2013 S\u00e3o Paulo]] champions [[Santos FC]], which Real Madrid won 5\u20133.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoria.bn.br/DocReader/docreader.aspx?bib=386030&pasta=ano+195&pesq=Santos+e+Real+Madrid|title=Ultima Hora (RJ) \u2013 1951 a 1984 \u2013 DocReader Web|website=memoria.bn.br}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoria.bn.br/DocReader/docreader.aspx?bib=386030&pasta=ano+195&pesq=Santos+e+Real+Madrid|title=Ultima Hora (RJ) \u2013 1951 a 1984 \u2013 DocReader Web|website=memoria.bn.br}}</ref>\n\nCreated in 1960 at the initiative of the European confederation ([[UEFA]]), with CONMEBOL's support, the ''European/South American Cup'', known also as the Intercontinental Cup, was contested by the holders of the European Champion Clubs\u2019 Cup and the winners of its newly established South American equivalent, the Copa Libertadores. The competition was not officially endorsed by FIFA,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pt.uefa.com/MultimediaFiles/Download/EuroExperience/uefaorg/Publications/01/59/87/45/1598745_DOWNLOAD.pdf|title=UEFA Direct, n\u00ba 105, 2011, page 15. Access on 04/Feb/2013.}}</ref> and in 1961 they refused to allow it to take place unless the participants gave it a \"private friendly match\" status.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1961/06/03/pagina-2/1384381/pdf.html|title=Edici\u00f3n del Saturday 3 June 1961, P\u00e1gina 2 - Hemeroteca |website=hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com}}</ref> However, the competition went on regardless, with the endorsement of UEFA and CONMEBOL; both federations consider all editions of the tournament to have been official, and include them in their records.<ref name=\"uefa.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/teamsandplayers/teams/club=50051/profile/index.html|title=Real Madrid \u2013 UEFA|last=uefa.com|publisher=UEFA}}</ref><ref name=\"Carluccio\">{{cite web |url=http://historiayfutbol.obolog.com/copa-libertadores-america-25746 |title=\u00bfQu\u00e9 es la Copa Libertadores de Am\u00e9rica? |trans-title=What is the Copa Libertadore de Am\u00e9rica? |publisher=Historia y F\u00fatbol |date=2 September 2007 |accessdate=18 May 2010 |first=Jose |last=Carluccio |language=Spanish }}</ref><ref name=\"fifa.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=107/edition=4735/news/newsid=95645.html |title=Goodbye Toyota Cup, hello FIFA Club World Championship |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430044241/http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament%3D107/edition%3D4735/news/newsid%3D95645.html |archivedate=30 April 2011  }}</ref> It was the brainchild of UEFA president [[Henri Delaunay]], who also helped [[Jules Rimet]] in the realisation of the inaugural [[FIFA World Cup]] in [[1930 FIFA World Cup|1930]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/timvickery/2010/12/post.html |title= World Club Cup deserves respect |publisher=[[BBC]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/portuguese/noticias/2002/020329_copa30.shtml |title= World Club Cup deserves respect |work=[[BBC Brasil|British Broadcasting Corporation Brasil]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 | language=Portuguese}}</ref> Initially played over two legs, with a third match if required in the early years (when goal difference did not count), the competition had a rather turbulent existence. The [[1960 Intercontinental Cup|first winners]] of the competition were Spanish club [[Real Madrid]]. Real Madrid managed to hold Uruguayan side [[Pe\u00f1arol]] 0\u20130 in [[Montevideo]] and trounce the South Americans 5\u20131 in [[Madrid]] to win.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=512284.html |title= Intercontinental Cup 1960 |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"RSSSF 60\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/intconclub60.html |title= Intercontinental Cup 1960 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Real Madrid\">{{cite web |url=http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/es/Club/1193040475224/PalmaresTotal/Palmares.htm |title=Trofeos de F\u00fatbol |work=[[Real Madrid Club de F\u00fatbol]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20091003154110/http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/es/Club/1193040475224/PalmaresTotal/Palmares.htm |archivedate=3 October 2009  }}</ref> After the victory of Real Madrid in the first edition of the Intercontinental Cup, Barcelona newspaper ''El Mundo Deportivo'' hailed the Madrid team as the First World Champion Club, on the one hand pointing out that the competition \"did not include Africans, Asians and other countries part to FIFA\", on the other hand expressing doubt that these regions might present football of the same high quality of Europe and South America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1960/09/05/pagina-3/1384556/pdf.html|title=Edici\u00f3n del Monday 5 September 1960, P\u00e1gina 3 - Hemeroteca |website=hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com}}</ref> The Spaniards titled themselves ''world champions'' until FIFA stepped in and objected; citing that the competition did not include any other champions from the other confederations, FIFA stated that they can only claim to be intercontinental champions of a competition played between two organisations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1979/06/08/pagina-2/1055660/pdf.html?search=copa|title= La Copa Intercontinental, un perro sin amo|work=[[El Mundo Deportivo (newspaper)|El Mundo Deportivo]]|accessdate=2 July 2010|language= Spanish}}</ref> Pe\u00f1arol would appear again the following year and come out victorious after beating Portuguese club [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] on the playoff; after a 1\u20130 win by the Europeans in [[Lisboa]] and a 5\u20130 trashing by the South Americans, a playoff at the [[Estadio Centenario]] saw the home side squeeze a 2\u20131 win to become the first South American side to win the competition.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=514912.html |title= Intercontinental Cup 1960 |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"RSSSF 61\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/intconclub61.html |title= Intercontinental Cup 1961 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Pe\u00f1arol\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pe\u00f1arol.org/uc_100_1.html |title=Palmar\u00e9s: Resumen de t\u00edtulos oficiales del Club Atl\u00e9tico Pe\u00f1arol |work=[[Club Atl\u00e9tico Pe\u00f1arol]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language=Spanish |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018050235/http://www.xn--pearol-xwa.org/uc_100_1.html |archive-date=18 October 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn [[1962 Intercontinental Cup|1962]] the tournament grew more in worldwide attention after it was swept through the sublime football of a [[Santos FC|Santos]] team led by [[Pel\u00e9]], considered by some the best club team of all times.<ref>{{cite book |last=Cunha |first=Odir |title=Time dos Sonhos |trans-title=Dream Teams |year=2003 |ISBN=85-7594-020-1 |language=Portuguese }}</ref> ''[[Os Sant\u00e1sticos]]'', also known as ''O Bal\u00e9 Branco'' (or white ballet), which dazzled the world during that time and containing stars such as [[Gylmar dos Santos Neves|Gilmar]], [[Mauro Ramos|Mauro]], [[Meng\u00e1lvio Pedro Figueir\u00f3|Meng\u00e1lvio]], [[Coutinho]], and [[Jos\u00e9 Macia|Pepe]], won the title after defeating Benfica 3\u20132 in Rio de Janeiro and thrashing the Europeans 2\u20135 in their [[Est\u00e1dio da Luz (1954)|Est\u00e1dio da Luz]].<ref name=\"Reference 2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=512321.html |title= \nIntercontinental Cups 1962 and 1963 |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"RSSSF 62\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/intconclub62.html |title= Intercontinental Cup 1962 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Santos\">{{cite web|url=http://www.santosfc.com.br/historia/default.asp?id=18033&c=Hist%F3ria&st=T%EDtulos |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120913112005/http://www.santosfc.com.br/historia/default.asp?id=18033&c=Hist%F3ria&st=T%EDtulos |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 September 2012 |title=T\u00edtulos |work=[[Santos Futebol Clube]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language=Portuguese }}</ref> Santos would successfully defend the title in [[1963 Intercontinental Cup|1963]] after being pushed all the way by Milan. After each side won 4\u20132 at their respective home legs, a playoff match at the Maracan\u00e3 saw Santos keep the title after a tight 1\u20130 victory.<ref name=\"Reference 2\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/intconclub63.html |title= Intercontinental Cup 1963 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref> The competition had attracted the interest of other continents. The North and Central America confederation, CONCACAF, had asked, unsuccessfully, to participate.<ref name=\"Santos\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://pt.uefa.com/MultimediaFiles/Download/EuroExperience/uefaorg/Publications/01/59/87/45/1598745_DOWNLOAD.pdf |title=European Commissioner visits UEFA |work=[[UEFA|Union Europ\u00e9enne de Football Association]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref> Milan's [[Derby della Madonnina|fierce rivals]], Internazionale, would go on to win the [[1964 Intercontinental Cup|1964]] and [[1965 Intercontinental Cup|1965]] editions, beating [[Argentine Primera Division|Argentine]] club [[Club Atl\u00e9tico Independiente|Independiente]] on both occasions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=512096.html |title=Intercontinental Cups 1964 and 1965 |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212151955/http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid%3D512096.html |archivedate=12 February 2009  }}</ref><ref name=\"RSSSF 64\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/intconclub64.html |title= Intercontinental Cup 1964 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"RSSSF 65\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/intconclub65.html |title= Intercontinental Cup 1965 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.inter.it/aas/palmares/vitt?L=it&IDV=22 |title= Palmares: PRIMA COPPA INTERCONTINENTALE \u2013 1964 |work=[[Inter Milan|Football Club Internazionale Milano S.p.A]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language= Italian }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.inter.it/aas/palmares/vitt?L=it&IDV=23 |title= Palmares: SECONDA COPPA INTERCONTINENTALE \u2013 1965 |work=[[Inter Milan|Football Club Internazionale Milano S.p.A]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language= Italian }}</ref> Pe\u00f1arol gained revenge for their loss in 1960 by crushing Real Madrid 4\u20130 in aggregate in [[1966 Intercontinental Cup|1966]].<ref name=\"Pe\u00f1arol\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=514924.html |title= Intercontinental Cups 1966 |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"RSSSF 66\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/intconclub66.html |title= Intercontinental Cup 1966 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Rioplatense violence===\nHowever, as a result of the violence often practised in the Copa Libertadores by Argentine and Uruguayan clubs during the 1960s,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.campeoesdofutebol.com.br/libertadores_historia.html |title=Hist\u00f3ria da Libertadores |work= Campeones do Futebol |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language= Portuguese }}</ref> disagreements with CONMEBOL, the lack of financial incentives and the violent, brutal and controversial way the [[Brazil national football team|Brazilian national team]] was treated in the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]] by European teams, Brazilian football\u2014including its club sides\u2014declined to participate in international competitions in the late 1960s, including the Copa Libertadores and consequently the Intercontinental Cup. During this time, the competition became dogged by foul play.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/history/index.html |title=European-South American Cup |work=[[UEFA|Union Europ\u00e9enne de Football Association]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131208213557/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/history/index.html |archivedate=8 December 2013 }}</ref> Calendar problems, acts of brutality, even on the pitch, and boycotts tarnished its image, to the point of bringing into question the wisdom of organising it at all.\n\nThe [[1967 Intercontinental Cup|1967 game]] between [[Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n|Argentina]]'s [[Racing Club de Avellaneda|Racing Club]] and [[Scottish Premier League|Scotland]]'s [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] was a violent affair, with the third decisive game being dubbed \"The Battle of Montevideo\" after three players from the Scottish side and two from the Argentine side were sent off. A fourth Celtic player was also dismissed near the end of the game, but amid the chaos he got away with staying on.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=512264.html |title= Intercontinental Cup 1967 |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"RSSSF 67\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/intconclub67.html |title= Intercontinental Club Cup 1967 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.racingclub.com.ar/palmares/copa-intercontinental-1967/ |title=Copa Intercontinental 1967 |work=[[Racing Club de Avellaneda]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language= Spanish }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.waterstones.com/waterstonesweb/products/brian+belton/the+battle+of+montevideo/6023862/ |title= The Battle of Montevideo: Celtic Under Siege |work=[[Waterstones]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Nestor Combin 1969.jpeg|thumb|left|150px|[[A.C. Milan]]'s [[N\u00e9stor Combin]] was left bloodied and unconscious after a brutal series against [[Estudiantes de La Plata]]]]\nThe [[1968 Intercontinental Cup|following season]], Argentine side [[Estudiantes de La Plata]] faced [[English First Division|England]]'s [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in which the return leg saw Estudiantes come out on top of a bad-tempered series.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=512037.html |title=Intercontinental Cup 1968 |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106142458/http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid%3D512037.html |archivedate=6 November 2012  }}</ref><ref name=\"RSSSF 68\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/intconclub68.html |title= Intercontinental Club Cup 1968 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edelpoficial.com.ar/portal/club/titulos.mfw |title=Titulos |work=[[Club Estudiantes de La Plata]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language=Spanish |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120423114721/http://www.edelpoficial.com.ar/portal/club/titulos.mfw |archive-date=23 April 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> But it was the events of [[1969 Intercontinental Cup|1969]] which damaged the competition's integrity.<ref name=\"Reference 9\">{{cite web |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/story?id=853334&sec=global&root=global&cc=5901 |title= Estudiantes leave their mark |work=[[ESPN FC|Entertainment and Sports Programming Network Football Club]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 }}</ref> After a 3\u20130 win at [[San Siro]], Milan went to [[Buenos Aires]] to play Estudiantes at [[Estadio Alberto J. Armando|''La Bombonera'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=512172.html |title=Intercontinental Cup 1969 |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124074911/http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid%3D512172.html |archivedate=24 January 2010  }}</ref><ref name=\"RSSSF 69\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/intconclub69.html |title= Intercontinental Club Cup 1969 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Reference 8\">{{cite web |url=http://www.acmilan.com/it/club/palmares/ci1969 |title=Coppa Intercontinentale 1969 |work=[[Associazione Calcio Milan]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 | language= Italian}}</ref> Estudiantes' players booted balls at the Milan team as they warmed up and hot coffee was poured on the Italians as they emerged from the tunnel by Estudiantes' fans. Estudiantes resorted to inflicting elbows and allegedly even needles at the Milanese team in order to intimidate them. [[Pierino Prati]] was knocked unconscious and continued for a further 20 minutes despite suffering from a mild concussion. Estudiantes goalkeeper Alberto Poletti also punched [[Gianni Rivera]], but the most vicious treatment was reserved for [[N\u00e9stor Combin]], an Argentinean-born striker, who had faced accusations of being a traitor as he was on the opposite side of the intercontinental match.<ref name=\"Reference 9\" /><ref name=\"Reference 10\">{{cite web |url=http://www.storiedicalcio.altervista.org/milan_estudiantes_1969.html |title= Coppa Intercontinentale 1969: Estudiantes-Milan, sfida selvaggia |work=Storie di Calcio |accessdate=2 July 2010 | language= Italian}}</ref><ref name=\"Reference 11\">{{cite web |url=http://www.futbolprimera.es/2009/02/10/partidos-inolvidables-estudiantes-milan-final-intercontinental-19691970 |title= Partidos inolvidables: Estudiantes \u2013 Milan (Final Intercontinental 1969/1970) |work=F\u00fatbol Primera |accessdate=2 July 2010 | language= Spanish}}</ref>\n\nCombin was kicked in the face by Poletti and later had his nose and cheekbone broken by the elbow of [[Ram\u00f3n Aguirre Su\u00e1rez]]. Bloodied and broken, Combin was asked to return to the pitch by the referee but fainted. While unconscious, Combin was arrested by Argentine police on a charge of draft dodging, having not undertaken military service in the country. The player was forced to spend a night in the cells, eventually being released after explaining he had fulfilled national service requirements as a French citizen.<ref name=\"Reference 9\" /> Estudiantes won the game 2\u20131 but Milan took the title on aggregate.<ref name=\"Reference 9\" /><ref name=\"Reference 8\" /><ref name=\"Reference 10\" /><ref name=\"Reference 11\" />\n\nItalian newspaper ''[[Gazzetta dello Sport]]'' dubbed it \"Ninety minutes of a man-hunt\". The Argentinean press responded with \"The English were right\" \u2013 a reference to [[Alf Ramsey]]'s famous description of the [[Argentina national football team]] as \"animals\" during the 1966 FIFA World Cup.<ref name=\"Reference 9\" /><ref name=\"Reference 10\" /><ref name=\"Reference 11\" /> The [[Asociaci\u00f3n del F\u00fatbol Argentino|Argentinean Football Association (AFA)]], under heavy international pressure, took stern action. Argentina's President, military dictator [[Juan Carlos Ongan\u00eda]], summoned Estudiantes delegate Oscar Ferrari and demanded \"the severest appropriate measures in defence of the good name of the national sport. [It was a] lamentable spectacle which breached most norms of sporting ethics\".<ref name=\"Reference 9\" /><ref name=\"Reference 10\" /><ref name=\"Reference 11\" /> Poletti was banned from the sport for life, Su\u00e1rez was banned for 30 games, and [[Eduardo Luj\u00e1n Manera|Eduardo Manera]] for 20 with the former and latter serving a month in jail.<ref name=\"Reference 9\" />\n\n===Degradation===\n\nDue to the brutality in these editions, FIFA was called into providing penalties and regulating the tournament. However, FIFA stated that it could not stipulate regulations in a competition that it did not organise. Though the competition was endorsed by UEFA and CONMEBOL as an official competition, Ren\u00e9 Courte, FIFA's General Sub-Secretary, wrote an facade article shortly afterwards stating that FIFA viewed the competition as a \"European-South American friendly match\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1967/03/16/pagina-8/931136/pdf.html?search=Intercontinental |title=La FIFA rehuye el bulto |trans-title=FIFA shuns the bulge |page=8 |work=El Mundo Deportivo |format=PDF |date=25 November 1967 |accessdate=6 March 2013 |language=Spanish }}</ref> Courte's statement was endorsed by then\u2013FIFA president Sir [[Stanley Rous]], who then stated that FIFA saw the Intercontinental Cup as a friendly match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1967/11/03/pagina-6/936416/pdf.html|title=Edici\u00f3n del Friday 3 November 1967, P\u00e1gina 6 - Hemeroteca |website=hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=GGgVawPscysC&dat=19671106&printsec=frontpage&hl=pt-BR|title=The Glasgow Herald \u2013 Pesquisa de arquivos de not\u00edcias Google|publisher=Google News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,ricerche/Itemid,3/|title=La Stampa \u2013 Consultazione Archivio|website=archiviolastampa.it}}</ref><ref name=\"hemeroteca.abc.es\">[http://hemeroteca.abc.es/nav/Navigate.exe/hemeroteca/madrid/abc/1967/11/03/097.html ABC Newspaper, Madrid (Spain), 3 Nov. 1967, page 97. Headline ''La FIFA no quiere saber nada de la final intercontinental, pues para ella es um partido \u201camistoso\u201d''. (In English: FIFA does not care about the Intercontinental final, as, for FIFA, it is a \"friendly match\".)  Contents in Spanish: ''Rous declar\u00f3 em um almuerzo de redactores esportivos que los partidos anuales para el t\u00edtulo intercontinental \u2013 entre los ganadores de la Copa de Europa y de America del Sur \u2013 est\u00e1 considerados oficialmente como encontros amistosos.  ....   Rous anadi\u00f3 que otras Federaciones, la Asiatica y de Americas Central y del Norte \u2013 han solicitado la participacion de sus clubs campeones en la Copa Intercontinental . Se oponen a ello \u2013 dijo el \u2013 las federaciones Europea y Sudamericana  ...  Sigui\u00f3 diciendo Sir Stanley que espera que se estudie todo lo relacionado con la competicion en la proxima Asemblea General de la FIFA: \u201cSi se aprueba, la competicion se desarrollaria a partir de entonces bajo la tutela del organismo mundial que presido\u201d, finaliz\u00f3 diciendo Sir Stanley Rous'' ...  (English translation: Rous stated, during a lunch with sports writers, that the annual matches for the intercontinental cup \u2013 between the winners of the European Cup and the South American one- are officially considered as friendly fixtures ... Rous also said that other Federations, the Asian and the North-Central American one- have requested the participation of their champion clubs in the Intercontinental Cup. According to Rous, the European and South American federations are opposed to it ...  Sir Stanley kept on saying that he expects that everything related to the competition should be studied in the next FIFA General Assembly: \"If approved, the competition would go on from then on under the auspices of the world organisation I preside\", concluded Sir Stanley.)]</ref> After these controversial statements, Madrid newspaper ''ABC'' then pointed out that, though the Intercontinental Cup was not officially endorsed by FIFA, it was endorsed by UEFA and CONMEBOL, therefore being an \"intercontinental jurisdiction\" cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hemeroteca.abc.es/nav/Navigate.exe/hemeroteca/madrid/abc/1967/11/08/087.html|title=ABC (Madrid) \u2013 08/11/1967, p. 87 \u2013 ABC.es Hemeroteca|website=ABC|location=Spain}}</ref> However, with the Asian and North-Central American club competitions in place, FIFA opened the idea of supervising the competition if it included those confederations, which was met with a negative response from its participating confederations, UEFA and CONMEBOL. According to [[Stanley Rous]], [[CONCACAF]] and the Asian Football Confederation had requested their participation in the Intercontinental Cup, which was rejected by UEFA and CONMEBOL.<ref name=\"Reference 12\">{{cite web |url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1967/11/01/pagina-4/931628/pdf.html?search=intercontinental%20fifa |title= La Copa Intercontinental de futbol debe ser oficial |work=[[El Mundo Deportivo (newspaper)|El Mundo Deportivo]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language= Spanish }}</ref><ref name=\"Reference 13\">{{cite web |url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1967/03/16/pagina-8/931136/pdf.html?search=Intercontinental |title= La FIFA rehuye el bulto |work=[[El Mundo Deportivo (newspaper)|El Mundo Deportivo]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language= Spanish }}</ref><ref name=\"Reference 14\">{{cite web |url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1966/07/27/pagina-6/936416/pdf.html?search=intercontinental |title= La FIFA, no controla la Intercontinental |work=[[El Mundo Deportivo (newspaper)|El Mundo Deportivo]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language= Spanish }}</ref><ref name=\"hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com\">{{cite web |url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1969/07/25/pagina-10/966431/pdf.html?search= |title= El proyecto de Copa del Mundo se discutira en M\u00e9jico |work=[[El Mundo Deportivo (newspaper)|El Mundo Deportivo]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language= Spanish }}</ref><ref name=\"\u00bfNueva Copa Intercontinental\">{{cite web |url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1970/01/08/pagina-13/949785/pdf.html?search=Copa |title= \u00bfNueva Copa Intercontinental? |work=[[El Mundo Deportivo (newspaper)|El Mundo Deportivo]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language= Spanish }}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web |url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1970/01/08/pagina-13/949785/pdf.html?search=Copa |title= La Copa del Mundo Inter-clubs se amplia |work=[[El Mundo Deportivo (newspaper)|El Mundo Deportivo]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language= Spanish}}</ref> Nevertheless, some European champions started to decline participation in the tournament after the events of 1969.<ref name=\"Reference 18\" />\n\nEstudiantes would face [[Eredivisie|Dutch side]] [[Feyenoord]] the [[1970 Intercontinental Cup|following season]], which saw the Europeans victorious. [[Oscar Malbernat]] ripped off [[Joop van Daele]]'s glasses and trampled on them claiming that he was \"not allowed to play with glasses\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=512045.html |title=Intercontinental Cup 1970 |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081209100426/http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid%3D512045.html |archivedate=9 December 2008  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/intconclub70.html |title= Intercontinental Cup 1970 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/history/season=1970/intro.html|title=1970: Feyenoord unfazed by Estudiantes|publisher=[[UEFA|Union des Associations Europ\u00e9ennes de Football]]|date=2 March 1980|accessdate=17 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112044325/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/history/season=1970/intro.html|archive-date=12 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.feyenoord.nl/pages/newsdetail/s1/10010000037178-999-10010000000003.aspx |title=Feyenoord viert veertigjarig jubileum winst Wereldbeker |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language=Dutch |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100911154733/http://www.feyenoord.nl/pages/newsdetail/s1/10010000037178-999-10010000000003.aspx |archive-date=11 September 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Dutch side [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]], [[1970-71 European Cup|European champions of 1971]], would decline to face [[Uruguayan Primera Divisi\u00f3n|Uruguay]]'s [[Club Nacional de Football|Nacional]] due to violence in previous editions, which resulted in European Cup runners-up, [[Superleague Greece|Greek]] side [[Panathinaikos FC|Panathinaikos]], participating.<ref name=\"Reference 19\">{{cite web\n |url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=512202.html\n |title=Intercontinental Cup 1971\n |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]]\n |accessdate=2 July 2010\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625133802/http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid%3D512202.html\n |archivedate=25 June 2012\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Reference 20\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/intconclub71.html |title= Intercontinental Cup 1971 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Reference 21\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.com.uy/mvdcms/uc_3394_1.html |title= Copa Intercontinental 1971 |work=[[Club Nacional de Football]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language= Spanish}}</ref> Nacional won the series 3\u20132 on aggregate.<ref name=\"Reference 19\" /><ref name=\"Reference 20\" /><ref name=\"Reference 21\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/history/season=1971/intro.html |title=1971: Artime puts paid to Panathinaikos |work=[[UEFA|Union Europ\u00e9enne de Football Association]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112044407/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/history/season=1971/intro.html |archive-date=12 January 2016 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ajax-selectie presenteert zich aan de pers, staand v.l.n. Suurbier, Stuy, Keizer, Bestanddeelnr 925-7435.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Dutch team [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] won the 1972 series v. Argentine club Independiente]]\nAjax participated in [[1972 Intercontinental Cup|1972]] against Independiente.<ref name=\"Reference 22\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=510713.html |title=Intercontinental Cup 1972 |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100622003141/http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid%3D510713.html |archivedate=22 June 2010  }}</ref><ref name=\"Reference 23\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/intconclub72.html |title= Intercontinental Cup 1972 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Ajax\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ajax.nl/De-Club/Erelijst-1.htm |title=Erelijst |work=[[Amsterdamsche Football Club Ajax]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language=Dutch |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101115021953/http://www.ajax.nl/De-Club/Erelijst-1.htm |archivedate=15 November 2010  }}</ref> The team's arrival at Buenos Aires was extremely hostile: Johan Cruyff received several death threats from Independiente's local fan firms.<ref name=\"Reference 30\">{{cite web |url=http://footballjourney1.blogspot.com/2009/07/super-cup-was-last-trophy-ajax-won-in.html |title= The Super Cup was the last trophy Ajax... |work=Football Journey |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref> Due to the indifference from the Argentine police, Ajax manager [[\u015etefan Kov\u00e1cs]] appointed an organised emergency security detail for the ''Nederlandse meester'', headed by himself and team member [[Barry Hulshoff]], described as a big and burly man.<ref name=\"Reference 30\" /> In the first leg, Cruyff opened the scoring in [[Avellaneda]] at the 5th minute. As a result, [[Dante Mircoli]] retaliated with a vicious tackle a couple of minutes later; Cruyff was too injured to continue and the Dutch team found themselves being assaulted with tackles and punches.<ref name=\"Reference 22\" /><ref name=\"Reference 23\" /><ref name=\"Ajax\" /> Kov\u00e1cs had to convince his team to play on during half-time as his players wanted to withdraw.<ref name=\"Reference 22\" /><ref name=\"Reference 23\" /><ref name=\"Ajax\" /> Ajax squeezed a 1\u20131 tie and followed up with a 3\u20130 trounce in [[Amsterdam]] to win the Cup.<ref name=\"Reference 22\" /><ref name=\"Reference 23\" /><ref name=\"Ajax\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/history/season=1970/intro.html|title=1972: Cruyff comes good for Ajax|publisher=[[UEFA|Union des Associations Europ\u00e9ennes de Football]]|date=2 March 1980|accessdate=17 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112044325/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/history/season=1970/intro.html|archive-date=12 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Although Ajax were the defending champions, they again declined to participate [[1973 Intercontinental Cup|a year later]] after Independiente won the [[1973 Copa Libertadores|Libertadores again]], leaving it to [[Juventus]], [[1972-73 European Cup|European Cup runners-up]], to play a single-match final won by the Argentines.<ref name=\"Reference 23\" /><ref name=\"Ajax\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=512084.html |title=Intercontinental Cup 1973 |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080306222942/http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid%3D512084.html |archivedate=6 March 2008  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/history/season=1973/intro.html|title=1973: Independiente resist Juve challenge|publisher=[[UEFA|Union des Associations Europ\u00e9ennes de Football]]|date=2 March 1980|accessdate=17 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112044446/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/history/season%3D1973/intro.html|archive-date=12 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 1973, French newspaper ''[[L'\u00c9quipe]]'', which helped to bring about the birth of the European Cup, volunteered to sponsor a Club World Cup contested by the champions of [[UEFA Champions League|Europe]], [[Copa Libertadores|South America]], [[CONCACAF Champions League|Central and North America]] and [[CAF Champions League|Africa]], the only continental club tournaments in existence at the time; the competition was to potentially take place in Paris between September and October 1974 with an eventual final to be held at the [[Parc des Princes]].<ref name=\"Reference 18\"/><ref name=\"Reference 18\">{{cite web |url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1979/11/22/pagina-15/1003523/pdf.html?search=copa |title= Europa ha desvalorizado la Copa Intercontinental |work=[[El Mundo Deportivo (newspaper)|El Mundo Deportivo]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language= Spanish }}</ref><ref name=\"Reference 7\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/newsfiles/240459.pdf |title= European Cup: 50 Years |work=[[UEFA|Union Europ\u00e9enne de Football Association]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1973/11/29/pagina-13/1002908/pdf.html?search=concacaf |title= Una ide para los cinco campeones de cada continente |work=[[El Mundo Deportivo (newspaper)|El Mundo Deportivo]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language= Spanish }}</ref><ref name=\"Reference 16\">{{cite web |url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1968/01/06/pagina-4/989608/pdf.html?search= |title= Una copa mundial de clubs con los campeones de Europa, \u00c1frica, Sudam\u00e9rica y Am\u00e9rica Central |work=[[El Mundo Deportivo (newspaper)|El Mundo Deportivo]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language= Spanish }}</ref> The proposal, supported by the [[CONMEBOL|South Americans]],<ref name=\"Reference 18\" /> was dismissed due to the negativity of the [[UEFA|Europeans]].<ref name=\"Reference 16\" />\n\n[[Bundesliga|West German]] club [[Bayern Munich]] also declined to play in [[1974 Intercontinental Cup|1974]] as Independiente again qualified to participate.<ref name=\"Reference 24\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=510737.html |title=Intercontinental Cup 1974 |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091204133633/http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid%3D510737.html |archivedate=4 December 2009  }}</ref><ref name=\"Reference 25\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/intconclub74.html |title= Intercontinental Cup 1974 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clubatleticodemadrid.com/Web/gestion/museo/trofeos.htm |title= Sala de Trofeos |work=[[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid|Club Atl\u00e9tico de Madrid, S.A.D.]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language= Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/history/season=1974/intro.html|title=1974: Aragon\u00e9s brings joy to Atl\u00e9tico|publisher=[[UEFA|Union des Associations Europ\u00e9ennes de Football]]|date=2 March 1980|accessdate=17 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112044523/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/history/season=1974/intro.html|archive-date=12 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[1973-74 European Cup|European Cup runners-up]] [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] from [[Spanish Primera Divisi\u00f3n|Spain]] won the competition 2\u20131 on aggregate.<ref name=\"Reference 24\" /><ref name=\"Reference 25\" /> Once again, Independiente qualified to participate in 1975; this time, both finalists of the [[1974-75 European Cup|European Cup]] declined to participate and the competition was not played.<ref name=\"Reference 27\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablest/toyota.html |title= Intercontinental Cup |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref> That same year, ''L'\u00c9quipe'' tried, once again, to create a Club World Cup, in which the participants would have been: the four semifinalists of the European Cup, both finalists of the Copa Libertadores, as well as the African and [[AFC Champions League|Asian]] champions. However, UEFA declined once again and the proposal failed.<ref name=\"Reference 17\">{{cite web |url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1973/11/29/pagina-13/1002908/pdf.html?search=concacaf |title= Una idea para los cinco campeones de cada continente |work=[[El Mundo Deportivo (newspaper)|El Mundo Deportivo]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language= Spanish }}</ref>\n\nIn [[1976 Intercontinental Cup|1976]], when Brazilian side [[Cruzeiro Esporte Clube|Cruzeiro]] won the Copa Libertadores, the [[1975-76 European Cup|European champions]] Bayern Munich willingly participated, with the Bavarians winning 2\u20130 on aggregate. In an interview with ''[[Jornal do Brasil]]'', Bayern's manager [[Dettmar Cramer]] denied that Bayern's refusal to dispute the 1974 and 1975 Intercontinental Cups were a result of the rivals being Argentine teams. He claimed it was a scheduling impossibility, rather, which kept the Germans from participating. He also stated that the competition was not economically rewarding due to the team's fan base's disinterest in the Cup. To cover the costs of playing the first leg in [[Munich]]'s [[Olympiastadion (Munich)|Olympiastadion]], the organizers needed to have a minimum of 25,000 spectators. However, due to heavy snow and cold weather, only 18,000 showed up. Because of this deficit, Cramer stated that if Bayern were to win the European Cup again, they would decline to participate as it held no assurances of income.<ref name=\"Reference 26\">{{cite web |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=0qX8s2k1IRwC&dat=19761222&printsec=frontpage&hl=pt-BR |title= Ta\u00e7a n\u00e3o interessa mais aos alem\u00e3es (page 20) |work=[[Jornal do Brasil]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language= Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Boca borussia 1978.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Argentine Boca Juniors played West German [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]] after European champions [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] declined to participate in the 1977 edition]]\nArgentine side [[Boca Juniors]] qualified for the [[1977 Intercontinental Cup|1977]] and 1978 editions, for which the European champions, [[English Premier League|English]] club [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], declined to participate on both occasions. In 1977, Boca Juniors defeated [[1976-77 European Cup|European Cup runners-up]], [[German Bundesliga|German]] club [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]], 5\u20132 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=510893.html |title=Intercontinental Cup 1977 |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090530233900/http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid%3D510893.html |archivedate=30 May 2009  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/intconclub77.html |title= Intercontinental Cup 1977 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bocajuniors.com.ar/el-club/titulos#1977_intercontinental |title=El Club: Titulos |work=[[Club Atl\u00e9tico Boca Juniors]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100608184737/http://www.bocajuniors.com.ar/el-club/titulos#1977_intercontinental |archivedate=8 June 2010  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/history/season=1977/intro.html|title=1977: Boca Juniors brush aside M\u00f6nchengladbach|publisher=[[UEFA|Union des Associations Europ\u00e9ennes de Football]]|date=2 March 1980|accessdate=17 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112044642/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/history/season=1977/intro.html|archive-date=12 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Boca Juniors declined to face [[Belgian Pro League|Belgian]] club [[Club Brugge K.V.|Brugge]] in 1978 leaving that edition undisputed.<ref name=\"Reference 27\" /> [[Paraguayan Primera Division|Paraguay]]'s [[Club Olimpia|Olimpia]] won the [[1979 Intercontinental Cup|1979]] edition against [[1978-79 European Cup|European Cup runners-up]], [[Allsvenskan|Swedish]] side [[Malm\u00f6 FF]], after winning both legs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=514900.html |title=Intercontinental Cup 1979 |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023221452/http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid%3D514900.html |archivedate=23 October 2012  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/intconclub79.html |title= Intercontinental Cup 1979 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/history/season=1979/intro.html|title=1979: Club Olimpia overpower Malm\u00f6|publisher=Union des Associations Europ\u00e9ennes de Football|date=2 March 1980|accessdate=17 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112044718/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/eusa/history/season=1979/intro.html|archive-date=12 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=514900.html|title=Intercontinental Cup 1979|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association|accessdate=17 December 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023221452/http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid%3D514900.html|archivedate=23 October 2012}}</ref> However, the competition had greatly declined in prestige. After the 0\u20131 win of the South Americans in the first leg at [[Malm\u00f6]], which saw fewer than 5,000 Swedish fans turn up, Spanish newspaper ''[[Mundo Deportivo (newspaper)|El Mundo Deportivo]]'' called the Cup \"a dog without an owner\".<ref name=\"Reference 18\" />\n\n{{Quote box|align=right|width=30%|quote=The truth is that the Intercontinental Cup is an adventitious competition without foundation.{{clarify|This seems to be a literal translation from Spanish that means nothing in English.|date=July 2018}} It has no known owner, it depends on a strange consensus and the interested clubs are not tempted to risk much for so little money, as evidenced by the attendance at the game in Malm\u00f6, played, of course, in absence of this year's champion, Nottingham Forest, by the Swedish team, finalist in one of the most boring and worst games played to cap off the European Cup since 1956.|source=<small>Spanish newspaper ''[[Mundo Deportivo (newspaper)|El Mundo Deportivo]]''<ref name=\"Reference 18\" /></small>|quoted=yes}}\n\nAccording to Brazilian newspaper ''[[O Estado de S\u00e3o Paulo]]'', the deal for the establishment of the [[Interamerican Cup]] was made in 1968 by CONMEBOL and CONCACAF, and established that the Interamerican Cup champion club would be entitled to represent the American continent in the Intercontinental Cup.<ref>[http://acervo.estadao.com.br/pagina/#!/19681010-28682-nac-0028-999-28-not/busca/campe%C3%B5es+Norte+America Brazilian newspaper ''O Estado de S\u00e3o Paulo'', 10/10/1968, page.28]</ref> According to the Mexican newspapers, after winning the 1977 and 1980 editions of the Interamerican Cup, Mexican clubs ''Am\u00e9rica'' and ''PUMAS Unam'', and the Mexican Football Association, demanded, unsuccessfully, to participate in the Intercontinental Cup.<ref>[http://hemeroteca.informador.com.mx/ Mexican neswspaper ''El Informador'', 14 and 16 April 1978, referring to Club America's claim to participate in the Intercontinental Cup.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506002334/http://hemeroteca.informador.com.mx/ |date=6 May 2016 }}</ref><ref>[http://h.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/Default/Skins/ElSiglo/Client.asp?Skin=ElSiglo&enter=true&AppName=2 Mexican newspaper ''El Siglo de Torr\u00e9on''. Archive. \"''Los Pumas Por La Copa Concacaf-EUFA''\" (15/May/1981, page 13).]</ref><ref>[http://h.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/Default/Skins/ElSiglo/Client.asp?Skin=ElSiglo&enter=true&AppName=2 Mexican newspaper ''El Siglo de Torr\u00e9on''. Archive. \"Mediocridad existente en el futbol del area de Concacaf.\" (29/August/1980, page 11).]</ref>\n\n===Rebirth in Japan===\n[[File:Club Nacional de Football del a\u00f1o 1980.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Uruguayan club [[Club Nacional de Football|Nacional]] won the first edition held in Japan, 1980]]\nSeeing the deterioration of the Intercontinental Cup, Japanese motor corporation [[Toyota]] took the competition under its wing. It created contractual obligations to have the Intercontinental Cup played in Japan once a year in which every club participating were obliged to participate or face legal consequences. This modern format breathed new air into the competition which saw a new trophy handed out along with the Intercontinental Cup, the Toyota Cup.\n\nTo protect themselves against the possibility of European withdrawals, Toyota, UEFA and every European Cup participant signed annual contracts requiring the eventual winners of the European Cup to participate at the Intercontinental Cup\u2014as a condition UEFA stipulated to the clubs' participation in the European Cup\u2014or risk facing an international lawsuit from UEFA and Toyota.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1992/12/29/pagina-8/1259619/pdf.html?search=Intercontinental |title=La negociaci\u00f3n ser\u00e1 dif\u00edcil |trans-title=Negotiations will be difficult |page=8 |last1=Aguilar |first1=Francesc |work=El Mundo Deportivo |format=PDF |date=18 September 1992|accessdate=6 March 2013 |language=Spanish }}</ref>\n\nThe first Toyota Cup was held in [[1980 Intercontinental Cup|1980]] which saw Uruguay's Nacional triumph over [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]. The 1980s saw a domination by South American sides as Brazil's [[Clube de Regatas Flamengo|Flamengo]] and Gr\u00eamio, Uruguay's Nacional and Pe\u00f1arol, Argentina's Independiente and River Plate take the spoils once each after Nacional's victory in 1980. Only Juventus, [[FC Porto|Porto]] and Milan managed to bring the trophy to the European continent. In that decade, the English [[The Football Association|Football Association]] tried organising a Club World Cup sponsored by promoting company West Nally only to be shot down by UEFA.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1983/04/20/pagina-20/1441398/pdf.html?search=mundial |title= La Copa Intercontinental el 11-D en Tokio: No habra una Copa Mundial de Clubes |work=[[El Mundo Deportivo (newspaper)|El Mundo Deportivo]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |language= Spanish}}</ref>\n\nThe 1990s proved to be a decade dominated by European teams, as Milan, Red Star Belgrade, Ajax, Juventus, Real Madrid, Manchester United, and newcomers [[Borussia Dortmund]] of Germany were fuelled to victory by their economic powers and heavy poaching of South American stars. Only three titles went to South America, as [[S\u00e3o Paulo Futebol Clube|S\u00e3o Paulo]] and Argentina's [[Club Atl\u00e9tico V\u00e9lez S\u00e1rsfield|V\u00e9lez S\u00e1rsfield]] came out the winners, each of them defeating Milan, with S\u00e3o Paulo's inaugural win being over Barcelona. The 2000s would see Boca Juniors win the competition twice for South America, while European victories came from Bayern Munich, Real Madrid, and Porto. The [[2004 Intercontinental Cup]] proved to be the last edition, as the competition was merged with the [[FIFA Club World Cup]].\n\n==International participation==\nAll the winning teams from Intercontinental Cup are regarded as de facto \"World club champions\".<ref name=\"FIFA Activity Report 2005\">{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=April 2004 \u2013 May 2005|title=FIFA Club World Championship TOYOTA Cup: Solidarity \u2013 the name of the game|url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/affederation/administration/01/68/21/16//activityreport2005en.pdf|url-status=dead|format=PDF|journal=FIFA Activity Report 2005|location=Zurich|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association|volume=|page=60|pages=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011001522/http://www.fifa.com/mm/document/affederation/administration/01/68/21/16//activityreport2005en.pdf|archivedate=11 October 2012|accessdate=17 December 2012|via=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=107/edition=4735/news/newsid=95645.html |title=Goodbye Toyota Cup, hello FIFA Club World Championship |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=10 December 2004 |accessdate=24 December 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430044241/http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament%3D107/edition%3D4735/news/newsid%3D95645.html |archivedate=30 April 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=107/edition=4735/news/newsid=99481.html |title=Ten tips on the planet's top club tournament |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=28 July 2005 |accessdate=28 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430044223/http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament%3D107/edition%3D4735/news/newsid%3D99481.html |archivedate=30 April 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=107/edition=4735/news/newsid=101662.html |title=We are the champions |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=1 December 2005 |accessdate=28 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430044235/http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament%3D107/edition%3D4735/news/newsid%3D101662.html |archivedate=30 April 2011  }}</ref> According to some texts on FIFA.com, due to the superiority at sporting level of the European and South American clubs to the rest of the world, reflected earlier in the tournament for national teams, the winning clubs of the Intercontinental Cup were named world champions and can claim to be symbolic World champions,<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/news/y=2005/m=12/news=are-the-champions-101662.html Text ''We Are The Champions''. 01/12/2005. FIFA site. Accessed on 04/feb/2013: clubs that have been '''''NAMED''''' world champions]</ref><ref>[https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/news/y=2005/m=12/news=ten-things-you-never-knew-101851.html Text  ''Ten things you never knew...'' FIFA site. Accessed on 15/12/2015.  \"Among this year's six representatives, Brazil's Sao Paulo are the only team that CAN CLAIM to have been world champions.\"]</ref> in a \"symbolic\" club world championship,<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/news/y=2004/m=12/news=goodbye-toyota-cup-hello-fifa-club-world-championship-95645.html  ''Goodbye Toyota Cup, hello FIFA Club World Championship'',  FIFA site. Accessed on 10 December 2004. Accessed on 08/03/2015: With the passage of time, it became apparent that it was unrealistic to continue to confer the '''''SYMBOLIC''''' title of \"club world champion\" on the basis of a single match between the European and South American champions.]</ref> while the FIFA Club World Cup would have another dimension,<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/news/y=2004/m=12/news=goodbye-toyota-cup-hello-fifa-club-world-championship-95645.html Text ''Goodbye Toyota Cup, hello FIFA Club World Championship'', on FIFA site. Access on 08/mar/2015: \"As of 2005, the Toyota Cup, traditionally a one-off match between the champions of Europe and South America, will take on a '''''WHOLE NEW DIMENSION''''' when it becomes the FIFA Club World Championship, disputed by the champion clubs from all six continents.\"]</ref> as the \"true\" world club showdown,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140407142155/http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/clubworldcup/japan2005/news/index%2Cpage%3D13.htmx Text ''Japan welcomes the world with open arms'', from FIFA site, recovered by Way Back Machine. Text of 28 July 2005. Accessed (recovery) on 31/12/2015. In the list of texts referring to the 2005 FIFA Club World Cup, this text brings as subtitle: ... Brought up watching the annual Europe-South America clash, Japanese fans are counting the days to the kick off of the '''''TRUE''''' world club showdown.]</ref><ref>[https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/news/y=2004/m=12/news=goodbye-toyota-cup-hello-fifa-club-world-championship-95645.html  ''Goodbye Toyota Cup, hello FIFA Club World Championship'',  FIFA site. Accessed on 10 December 2004. Accessed on 08/03/2015: According to the new format, which enters into force in 2005, once again in Japan, the respective winners of the six \"champions cups\" of each confederation will qualify for the FIFA Club World Championship. \"I am convinced that this is the best formula for everyone,\" argues Michel Platini, a FIFA Executive Committee member and former Toyota Cup winner from 1985. \"It won't make the clubs' trips any longer, but by playing an extra game, the club crowned this time will be '''''TRUE''''' world champions,\" continued the former Juventus playmaker.]</ref><ref>[https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/news/y=2005/m=7/news=continental-champions-prepare-for-tokyo-draw-99485.html Text ''Continental champions prepare for Tokyo draw'', FIFA site, 28 July 2005. Accessed on 08/March/2015: Initially a one-off contest between the champions of South America and Europe,  the Toyota Cup, which superseded the Intercontinental Cup in 1980,  has been revamped by FIFA to reach out to all confederations and associations across the globe so the winners may '''''TRULY''''' be regarded as the best club side in the world.]</ref> created because, with the passage of time and the development of football outside Europe and South America, it had become \"unrealistic\" to continue to confer the symbolic title of world champion upon the winners of the Intercontinental Cup,<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/news/y=2004/m=12/news=goodbye-toyota-cup-hello-fifa-club-world-championship-95645.html  ''Goodbye Toyota Cup, hello FIFA Club World Championship'',  FIFA site. Accessed on 10 December 2004. Accessed on 08/03/2015: ''With the passage of time, it became apparent that it was unrealistic to continue to confer the symbolic title of \"club world champion\" on the basis of a single match between the European and South American champions''.]</ref> the idea to expand it being mentioned for the first time in 1967 by Stanley Rous as CONCACAF and the [[Asian Football Confederation|AFC]] had established their continental club competitions and requested the participation,<ref name=\"hemeroteca.abc.es\"/><ref name=\"Reference 12\"/><ref name=\"Reference 13\"/><ref name=\"Reference 14\"/><ref name=\"hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com\"/><ref name=\"\u00bfNueva Copa Intercontinental\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> an expansion that was to occur only in 2000 through the [[2000 FIFA Club World Championship]]. Nevertheless, some European champions started to decline participation in the tournament after the events of 1969.<ref name=\"Reference 18\" /> Though \"symbolic\" or ''de facto'' as a club world championship,<ref name=\"fifa.com\"/> the Intercontinental Cup was an official title at interconfederation level, with both UEFA and CONMEBOL have always considered all editions of the competition as part of their official honours.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"uefa.com2\" />\n\nThroughout the history of football, various attempts have been made to organise a tournament that identifies \"the best club team in the world\" \u2013 such as the [[Football World Championship]], the [[Sir Thomas Lipton Trophy|Lipton Trophy]], the [[Copa Rio (international tournament)|Copa Rio]] and [[Peque\u00f1a Copa del Mundo]] \u2013 due to FIFA's lack of interest or inability to organise club competitions,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kassiesa.net/uefafiles/2004-uefa-50-years-european-cup.pdf|title=50 years of the European Cup|date=October 2004|work=Union des Associations Europ\u00e9ennes de Football|pages=7\u20139|format=PDF|accessdate=15 December 2011}}</ref> \u2013 the Intercontinental Cup is considered by FIFA as the predecessor<ref name=\"FIFA Activity Report 20052\">{{cite journal|date= April 2004 \u2013 May 2005|title=FIFA Club World Championship TOYOTA Cup: Solidarity \u2013 the name of the game|url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/affederation/administration/01/68/21/16//activityreport2005en.pdf|url-status=dead|format=PDF|journal=FIFA Activity Report 2005|location=Zurich|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association|page=62|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011001522/http://www.fifa.com/mm/document/affederation/administration/01/68/21/16//activityreport2005en.pdf|archivedate=11 October 2012|accessdate=17 December 2012}}</ref> to the FIFA Club World Cup, which was held for the first time in [[2000 FIFA Club World Championship|2000]].\n\n==FIFA recognition==\n\nOn 27 October 2017 FIFA Council, while not promoting statistical unification with the current World Cup, in respect to the history of the two tournaments<ref name=\"kit20172\">{{cite web|url=http://resources.fifa.com/mm/document/fifafacts/mencompcwc/02/67/91/87/statskit_fcwc2017_event_neutral.pdf|title=FIFA Club World Cup UAE 2017: Statistical Kit FIFA|pages=15, 40, 41, 42|format=PDF}}</ref> \n(which merged in 2005)<ref name=\"FIFA Activity Report 20053\">{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=April 2004 \u2013 May 2005|title=FIFA Club World Championship TOYOTA Cup: Solidarity \u2013 the name of the game|url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/affederation/administration/01/68/21/16//activityreport2005en.pdf|url-status=dead|format=PDF|journal=FIFA Activity Report 2005|location=Zurich|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association|volume=|page=60|pages=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011001522/http://www.fifa.com/mm/document/affederation/administration/01/68/21/16//activityreport2005en.pdf|archivedate=11 October 2012|accessdate=17 December 2012|via=}}</ref> has officilised (''[[de jure]]'') the world title recognising all the winners as official<ref name=\":F15232\"/><ref name=\":F154232\">For FIFA statute, official competitions are those for representative teams organized by FIFA or any confederation. Representative teams are usually national teams but also club teams that represent a confederation in the interconfederal competitions or a member association in a continental competition cfr. {{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/the-fifa-statutes-in-force-as-of-27-april-2016-2782908.pdf?cloudid=vga5sv1yxeayptzrdudx|title=FIFA Statutes, April 2016 edition|page=5|format=PDF}} cfr. {{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/statistical-kit-fifa-club-world-cup-uae-2018.pdf?cloudid=mkbo3nwk4btahl9gwtwl|title=FIFA Club World Cup UAE 2018: Statistical-kit|date=10 December 2018|page=13|format=PDF}} cfr. {{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/MultimediaFiles/Download/Regulations/uefaorg/Regulations/02/55/82/79/2558279_DOWNLOAD.pdf|title=2018/19 UEFA Champions League regulations|page=10|format=PDF}}</ref><ref name=\":F154233\">\u201cWhile it does not promote the statistical unification of tournaments, that is, has not absorbed to the Intercontinental Cup (merged with FIFA Club World Cup in 2005), FIFA is the only organization with worldwide jurisdiction over continental confederations and, then, the only one that can confer a title on that level, ergo the title was assigned by FIFA with Official Document to the winners of the Intercontinental Cup is legally a FIFA world title.\"  cfr. {{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/the-fifa-statutes-in-force-as-of-27-april-2016-2782908.pdf?cloudid=vga5sv1yxeayptzrdudx|title=FIFA Statutes, April 2016 edition|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=19|format=PDF|access-date=}} cfr.</ref> club world champions FIFA with the same status to the [[FIFA Club World Cup]] winners.<ref name=\":F154233\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/about-fifa/news/y=2017/m=10/news=fifa-council-approves-key-organisational-elements-of-the-fifa-world-cu-2917722.html|title=FIFA Council approves key organisational elements of the FIFA World Cup/ Recognition of all European and South American teams that won the Intercontinental Cup \u2013 played between 1960 and 2004 \u2013 as club world champions.|work=Fifa.com}}</ref><ref name=\"kit20182\">{{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/statistical-kit-fifa-club-world-cup-uae-2018.pdf?cloudid=mkbo3nwk4btahl9gwtwl|title=FIFA Club World Cup UAE 2018: Statistical-kit|date=10 December 2018|page=13|format=PDF}}</ref><ref name=\"kit20172\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/manchester-united-recognised-two-time-11419510|title=Manchester United recognised as two-time world club champions following FIFA ruling|work=Mirror.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/manchester-united/story/3246638/man-united-retrospectively-declared-1999-world-club-champions-by-fifa|title=Real Madrid are the most successful club across the history of the two competitions, with a total of five victories (2016).|work=Espn.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2017/12/1-0-sixth-club-world-cup|title=Real Madrid! Sixth Club World Cup!|work=Realmadrid.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.it/2017/10/28/fifa-decisione-storica-albo-oro-mondiale-per-club-va-riscritto/|title=Historical decision, register Club World Cup is rewritten.|work=Foxsports.it (in Italian)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/es/noticias/la-fifa-reconocio-a-los-ganadores-de-la-intercontinental/i72nwrb7zcnp12ymz0v9trinu|title=La FIFA reconoci\u00f3 a los ganadores de la Intercontinental como campeones mundiales|work=Goal.com (in Spanish; with documents.)}}</ref>\nFIFA changing only the conferred title,<ref name=\":F154233\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/about-fifa/news/y=2017/m=10/news=fifa-council-approves-key-organisational-elements-of-the-fifa-world-cu-2917722.html|title=FIFA Council approves key organisational elements of the FIFA World Cup/ Recognition of all European and South American teams that won the Intercontinental Cup \u2013 played between 1960 and 2004 \u2013 as club world champions.|work=Fifa.com}}</ref> also because for the FIFA Statute, the Intercontinental Cup was already an official competition<ref name=\":F15423\">For FIFA statute, official competitions are those for representative teams organized by FIFA or any confederation. Representative teams are usually national teams but also club teams that represent a confederation in the interconfederal competitions or a member association in a continental competition cfr. {{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/the-fifa-statutes-in-force-as-of-27-april-2016-2782908.pdf?cloudid=vga5sv1yxeayptzrdudx|title=FIFA Statutes, April 2016 edition|page=5|format=PDF}} cfr. {{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/statistical-kit-fifa-club-world-cup-uae-2018.pdf?cloudid=mkbo3nwk4btahl9gwtwl|title=FIFA Club World Cup UAE 2018: Statistical-kit|date=10 December 2018|page=13|format=PDF}} cfr. {{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/MultimediaFiles/Download/Regulations/uefaorg/Regulations/02/55/82/79/2558279_DOWNLOAD.pdf|title=2018/19 UEFA Champions League regulations|page=10|format=PDF}}</ref> unlike, for example, the ''King Fahd Cup'' which became the [[FIFA Confederations Cup]].<ref name=\":579\">The King Fahd Cup  was organized by the [[Fahd of Saudi Arabia | King Fahd]] and the Saudi Arabian Federation, therefore, according to the FIFA statute, it was initially played in an unofficial way. \u00abAccording to the FIFA statute, the official competitions are those for representative teams organized by FIFA or any confederation (not the national federations, which organize cups and championships in the country itself officially having only national jurisdiction) cfr. {{cita web|url=https://www.uefa.com/MultimediaFiles/Download/uefaorg/General/02/54/12/62/2541262_DOWNLOAD.pdf|title=UEFA Statutes|language=en|format=PDF|p=3}} Representative teams are usually national teams but also teams of clubs that represent a confederation in intercontinental competitions or a member association in confederal competitions.\u00bb cfr.{{cita web|language=en|title=Statistical kit FIFA Club World Cup UAE 2018|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/statistical-kit-fifa-club-world-cup-uae-2018.pdf?cloudid=mkbo3nwk4btahl9gwtwl|page=13|}} cfr. {{cita web|language=en|title=2018/19 UEFA Champions League regulations|url=https://www.uefa.com/MultimediaFiles/Download/Regulations/uefaorg/Regulations/02/55/82/79/2558279_DOWNLOAD.pdf|editor=UEFA|format=PDF|p=10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sefutbol.com/en/13-things-you-need-know-about-confederations-cup|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012175450/http://www.sefutbol.com/en/13-things-you-need-know-about-confederations-cup|url-status=dead|archive-date=12 October 2018|title=13 things you need to know about the Confederations Cup|date=24 June 2014|work=sefutbol.com}}</ref>\n\nAs it happened, for example, for the statistics of the [[Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A|Brazilian Championship]], there was the unification of the titles of champions (considered all official) differentiating the competitions ([[Torneio Roberto Gomes Pedrosa]], [[Ta\u00e7a Brasil]], [[Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A]]), organized by different federations ([[Federa\u00e7\u00e3o Paulista de Futebol|FPF]]\u2013[[Federa\u00e7\u00e3o de Futebol do Estado do Rio de Janeiro|FFD]] in 1967, [[Brazilian Sports Confederation|CBD]] from 1959 to 1978, [[Brazilian Football Confederation|CBF]] from 1979),<ref>{{cita web|url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/esporte/2018/11/por-que-o-palmeiras-e-decacampeao-veja-os-titulos-nacionais-do-clube.shtml|title=Por que o Palmeiras \u00e9 decacampe\u00e3o? Veja os t\u00edtulos nacionais do clube|author=Folha de S.Paulo|date=26 November 2018|language=pt}}</ref> in the list of winners issued by the main federation, the CBF.<ref>{{cite news|language=pt|url=https://www.cbf.com.br/futebol-brasileiro/noticias/campeonato-brasileiro-serie-a/palmeiras-nove-vezes-campeao-brasileiro|title=Palmeiras: nove vezes campe\u00e3o brasileiro|work=cbf.com.br|date=27 November 2016|author=Assessoria CBF}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/esporte/2018/11/por-que-o-palmeiras-e-decacampeao-veja-os-titulos-nacionais-do-clube.shtml|title=Por que o Palmeiras \u00e9 decacampe\u00e3o? Veja os t\u00edtulos nacionais do clube|work=Folha de S.Paulo|date=26 November 2018|language=pt}}</ref>Another similar case is that of the Argentine champions. Over the years seven different federations have organized the championship, the [[Argentine Football Association]] (AFA), that is the current Argentine federation, recognizes all titles as official.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afa.com.ar/institucional/campeones-primera-division.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150617061659/http://www.afa.com.ar/institucional/campeones-primera-division.php|url-status=dead|archive-date=17 June 2015|title=Campeones de Primera Divisi\u00f3n|author=SITIO OFICIAL DE LA ASOCIACI\u00d3N DEL F\u00daTBOL ARGENTINO|date=17 June 2015|work=afa.com.ar|language=es}}</ref>\n\n==Trophy==\nThe competition trophy bears the words ''\"Coupe Europ\u00e9enne-Sudamericaine\"'' (\"European-South American Cup\") at the top. At the base of the trophy, there is the round logo of UEFA and a map of South America in a circle.\n\nDuring the sponsorship by Toyota, the competition awarded an additional trophy, entitled ''\"Toyota Cup\"''. \n\n==Cup format==\nFrom 1960 to 1979, the Intercontinental Cup was played in two legs. Between 1960 and 1968, the cup was decided on points only, the same format used by CONMEBOL to determine the winner of the Copa Libertadores final through 1987. Because of this format, a third match was needed when both teams were equal on points. Commonly this match was host by the continent where the last game of the series was played. From 1969 through 1979, the competition adopted the European standard method of aggregate score, with [[away goals rule|away goals]].\n\nStarting in 1980, the final became a single match. Up until 2001, the matches were held at Tokyo's National Stadium. Finals since 2002 were held at the [[International Stadium Yokohama|Yokohama International Stadium]], also the venue of the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]] final.\n\n==Results==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n|-\n| width=\"40px\" bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\" align=\"center\"|\n| Match was won during [[Overtime (sports)#Association football (soccer)|extra time]]\n|-\n| width=\"40px\" bgcolor=\"#cedff2\" align=\"center\"|\n| Match was won on a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]]\n|-\n| width=\"40px\" bgcolor=\"#D0F0C0\" align=\"center\"|\u2021\n| Play-off match where teams were tied on points (1 win and 1 defeat each)\n|-\n| width=\"40px\" align=\"center\"|