onna Summer|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=1975|certyear=1976|refname=US Plat}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==Cover versions and samples==\n\n*The refrain \"Love to love you\" can be heard predominantly in the background of [[Diana Ross]]' 1976 hit \"[[Love Hangover]]\". \n*In [[1982]], Indian singer [[Sharon Prabhakar]] recorded a cover of the song in Hindi, entitled \"Aaj Ki Raat\" on her album \"Disco Mastana\", released on [[Multitone]] records.\n*An excerpt of the song was featured during the first episode of ''[[The Brady Bunch Hour|The Brady Bunch Variety Hour]]'' and a subsequent tell-all book about the show was titled \"[[Love to Love You Bradys]].\"<ref name=fakejan>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Love-You-Bradys-Bizarre-Variety/dp/1550228889/|title=amazon.com: Love to Love You Bradys: The Bizarre Story of the Brady Bunch Variety Hour|accessdate=June 6, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Digital Underground]] made the song the central sample of the song \"Freaks of the Industry\" on their 1990 debut album ''[[Sex Packets]]''.\n*[[Samantha Fox]] covered her tune into a medley with ''[[More, More, More]]'' from her 1991 album ''[[Just One Night (Samantha Fox album)|Just One Night]]''.\n*[[TLC (group)|TLC]] sampled the song on the album version of their 1999 song \"[[I'm Good At Being Bad]]\".\n*[[The Tom Tom Club]] recorded a cover for their 2000 album \"[[The Good, The Bad, and the Funky]].\"<ref>https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-good-the-bad-and-the-funky-mw0000088205</ref>\n*[[Beyonc\u00e9]] also sampled the refrain of the song for her hit \"[[Naughty Girl (Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles song)|Naughty Girl]]\" on her album ''[[Dangerously in Love]]'', which she performed live for the Fashion Rocks Awards 2004 <ref>[http://www.wat.tv/video/beyonce-naugthy-girl-live-1gm8x_2i4l5_.html Seen on April 4, 2013] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102231412/http://www.wat.tv/video/beyonce-naugthy-girl-live-1gm8x_2i4l5_.html |date=January 2, 2014 }}</ref>\n*French male model and singer [[Baptiste Giabiconi]] covered it as an adaptation and heavy sampling of the hit in 2016, but with added lyrics and new EDM arrangement. His version credited to mononym Giabiconi entered the French [[SNEP]] chart at #14 in July 2016.<ref>[http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Baptiste+Giabiconi&titel=Love+To+Love+You+Baby&cat=s LesCharts.com: Baptiste Giabiconi - \"Love To Love You Baby\" song page]</ref>\n* In 2018, the song was included in the Broadway musical ''[[Summer: The Donna Summer Musical]]''.\n\n==See also==\n*[[1975 in music]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|donna-summer|love-to-love-you-baby}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Donna Summer discography}}\n{{Jimmy Somerville}}\n{{No Doubt singles}}\n{{Tom Tom Club}}\n\n[[Category:1975 singles]]\n[[Category:1976 singles]]\n[[Category:1983 singles]]\n[[Category:Funk ballads]]\n[[Category:Donna Summer songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Dance Club Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:RPM Top Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Pete Bellotte]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Giorgio Moroder]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Donna Summer]]\n[[Category:Samantha Fox songs]]\n[[Category:Casablanca Records singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Pete Bellotte]]\n[[Category:1975 songs]]\n[[Category:GTO Records singles]]\n[[Category:Polar Music singles]]\n[[Category:Ariola Records singles]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records singles]]\n[[Category:1970s ballads]]\n[[Category:Songs banned by the BBC]]\n[[Category:Songs about sexuality]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1975 single by Donna Summer}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Love to Love You Baby\n| cover      = Love to Love You Baby by Donna Summer 1975 US vinyl A-side.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = A-side label of US vinyl single\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Donna Summer]]\n| album      = [[Love to Love You Baby (album)|Love to Love You Baby]]\n| B-side     = Need-a-Man Blues\n| released   = June 1975 (Netherlands, as \"'''Love to Love You'''\")<br />November 26, 1975 (Worldwide, as \"'''Love to Love You Baby'''\")\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Gramophone record|7-inch vinyl]]|[[12-inch single|12-inch vinyl]]}}\n| recorded   = 1974 (as \"Love to Love You\")<br/>May\u2013June 1975; [[Musicland Studios]] <small>([[Munich]], [[West Germany]])</small><br />(as \"Love to Love You Baby\")\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Disco]]|[[funk]]}}\n| length     = 16:49 <small>(Album version)</small>\n| label      = [[Oasis Records|Oasis]] <small>(United States/Canada)</small><br/>[[GTO Records|GTO]] <small>(United Kingdom)</small><br/>[[Polar Records|Polar]] <small>(Sweden)</small><br/>[[Ariola Records|Ariola]] <small>(Spain/Portugal)</small><br/>Interfusion <small>(Australia)</small><br/>[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]] <small>(France/Germany)</small><br/>[[Durium Records|Durium]] <small>(Italy)</small>\n| writer     = {{hlist|Donna Summer|[[Giorgio Moroder]]|[[Pete Bellotte]]}}\n| producer   = Pete Bellotte\n| prev_title = [[Lady of the Night (album)|Little Miss Fit]]\n| prev_year  = 1974\n| next_title = [[Virgin Mary (song)|Virgin Mary]]\n| next_year  = 1975\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     =\n | type       =\n | prev_title = [[Virgin Mary (song)|Virgin Mary]]\n | prev_year  = 1975\n | title      = Love to Love You Baby\n | year       = 1975\n | next_title = [[Could It Be Magic]]\n | next_year  = 1976\n}}\n {{Extra chronology\n | artist     =\n | type       =\n | prev_title = [[Protection (Donna Summer song)|Protection]]\n | prev_year  = 1983\n | title      = \"Love to Love You Baby\" (re-issue)\n | year       = 1983\n | next_title = [[She Works Hard for the Money]]\n | next_year  = 1983\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Love to Love You Baby'''\" is a song by American singer [[Donna Summer]] from her second studio album ''[[Love to Love You Baby (album)|Love to Love You Baby]]'' (1975). Produced by [[Pete Bellotte]], and written by Italian musician [[Giorgio Moroder]], Summer, and Bellotte, the song was first released as a [[Single (music)|single]] in the Netherlands on June 1975 as \"'''Love to Love You'''\" and then released worldwide on November 1975 as \"Love to Love You Baby\". It became one of the first [[disco]] hits to be released in an extended form.\n\nThe [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] named it one of the [[500 Songs That Shaped Rock and Roll]], Summer's only selection on this list.<ref>{{cite web |last=Henke\n |first=James |url=https://www.infoplease.com/arts-entertainment/music/500-songs-shaped-rock |title=500 Songs That Shaped Rock and Roll |publisher=[[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] |accessdate=March 2, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nBy 1975, Summer had been living in [[Germany]] for eight years and had participated in several musical theatre shows. She had also released an album in [[The Netherlands]] entitled ''[[Lady of the Night (album)|Lady of the Night]]'' (1974), written by [[Giorgio Moroder]] and [[Pete Bellotte]] and produced by Bellotte, which had given her a couple of hit singles. She was still a complete unknown in her home country when she suggested the lyric \"Love to Love You Baby\" to Moroder in 1975. He turned the lyric into a full [[disco]] song and asked Summer to record it. The full lyrics were somewhat explicit, and at first, Summer said she would only record it as a demo to give to someone else. However, Summer's erotic moans and groans impressed Moroder so much that he persuaded her to release it as her own song, and \"'''Love to Love You'''\" became a moderate hit in the [[Netherlands]].\n\nIn an interview in 1976, Summer responded to a number of questions that she claimed she'd been asked about the process of recording the song: \"Everyone's asking, 'Were you alone in the studio?' Yes, I was alone in the studio. 'Did you touch yourself?' Yes, well, actually I had my hand on my knee. 'Did you fantasize on anything?' Yes, on my handsome boyfriend Peter.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Donna Summer: 'The audience was groaning worse than I was' \u2013 a classic interview from the vaults|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/may/17/donna-summer-classic-interview|accessdate=9 June 2012 | location=London|work=The Guardian|first=Richard|last=Cromelin|date=17 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==International release and reception==\n\nA tape of the song was sent to [[Casablanca Records]] president [[Neil Bogart]] in the U.S., and he played it at a party at his home. Impressed with the track, Bogart continued to play it over and over all night. He later contacted Moroder and suggested that he make the track longer - possibly as long as 20 minutes. However, Summer again had reservations; she was not sure of all of the lyrics. Nevertheless, she imagined herself as an actress (namely [[Marilyn Monroe]])<ref name=\"blender\">[http://www.blender.com/guide/68500/greatest-songs-ever-love-to-love-you-baby.html \"The Greatest Songs Ever! Love to Love You Baby\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231054630/http://www.blender.com/guide/68500/greatest-songs-ever-love-to-love-you-baby.html |date=2010-12-31 }} Blender.com, 21 November 2006. Retrieved 2 July 2009.</ref> playing the part of someone in sexual ecstasy. The studio lights were dimmed so that Summer was more or less in complete darkness as she lay on the floor.\n\nThe final recording lasted over 16 minutes, and according to the [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]], contained 23 \"orgasms\".<ref name=\"blender\"/> By that point, the song was renamed \"Love to Love You Baby\". It took up the entire first side of the [[Love to Love You Baby (album)|album of the same name]], and edited versions were also found on 7\" vinyl.\n\nOriginally released in November 1975, the song became an international disco smash. In the U.S., it became Summer's first US Top 40 hit, spending two weeks at #2 on the ''Billboard'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]] chart in February 7 & 14 1976<ref>[[Joel Whitburn|Whitburn, Joel]] (2004). ''The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits'', 8th Edition (Billboard Publications), page 612.</ref> being held off the number one spot by [[Paul Simon]]'s \"[[50 Ways to Leave Your Lover]]\" and logged four weeks atop the ''Billboard'' [[Dance Club Songs]] chart,<ref>[[Joel Whitburn|Whitburn, Joel]] (2004). ''Hot Dance/Disco 1974-2003'', (Record Research Inc.), page 249.</ref> as well number three on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart.<ref>{{cite book |title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942-2004|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=556}}</ref>\n\nIn the UK, upon release in January 1976, the song reached #4<ref>[https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/Strange%20Magic Official Charts Company info] OfficialCharts.com. Retrieved 2 July 2009.</ref> on the [[UK Singles Chart]] in spite of the BBC's initial refusal to promote it. They also refused to play it.{{cn|date=September 2019}} As a result of the success of the song, Summer would be named \"the first lady of love,\" which labeled her with a sexually oriented, fantasy image from which she would struggle to free herself.{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\n[[Casablanca Records]] became responsible for the distribution of Summer's work in the U.S. Bogart was particularly keen for Summer to portray the image of the rich, powerful, sexy fantasy figure with which this song had labeled her.{{cn|date=September 2019}} Bogart and his wife Joyce (who also became Summer's manager) would become close friends with Summer once she returned to the United States. However, Bogart also began interfering with aspects of Summer's personal and professional life.{{cn|date=September 2019}} She would later become a [[born-again Christian]], leave disco, Casablanca and the Bogarts behind, and file a lawsuit against them.{{cn|date=September 2019}} Thereafter, Summer decided to exclude \"Love to Love You Baby\" from her concert playlists.{{cn|date=September 2019}} However, she reintroduced the song into her concert repertoire some 25 years later.\n\n==Impact and legacy==\n[[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] named the song one of the [[500 Songs That Shaped Rock and Roll]] in 1995.\n\n''[[VH1]]'' placed \"Love to Love You Baby\" at #63 in their list of '''100 Greatest Dance Songs''' in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2000/vh1dance.htm|title=Rock On The Net: VH1: 100 Greatest Dance Songs|website=www.rockonthenet.com}}</ref>\n\n''[[Slant Magazine]]'' ranked the song 10th in its 100 Greatest Dance Songs in 2006.<ref>{{cite journal |title=100 Greatest Dance Songs  |url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/100-greatest-dance-songs/P10|journal=[[Slant Magazine]] |date=30 January 2006 |accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Peter Shapiro (journalist)|Peter Shapiro]], a freelance British music journalist, the song was marked by \"little more than Donna Summer simulating an orgasm over a background of [[blaxploitation]] cymbals, [[wah-wah (music)|wah-wah]] guitars, a funky-butt clarinet riff, and some synth chimes.\" He continued, \"Love to Love You Baby\" [...] was extended into a seventeen-minute minisymphony at the behest of Casablanca Records chief Neil Bogart, who wanted a soundtrack for his sexual exploits.  The song reached number two in the American charts and was largely responsible for the development of the twelve inch single.\"<ref>Shapiro, Peter. Turn the Beat around : the Secret History of Disco. London, Faber and Faber, Inc., 2009.</ref>\n\nDonna Summer has since been forced to stop performing \"Love to Love You\" live because, \"Riots broke out [...] [She] was in a tent in Italy, 5,000 men, almost no women, and was doing 'Love to Love You, Baby,' fairly scantily clad, and the guys got so wrapped up that they began to push the stage back. And [she] had to run off the stage, to [her] trailer out the back. And they came to the trailer and started to rock it. [She] just thought, 'I'm going to die today, I'm not going to get out of here.' It's not the kind of song you just want to throw out there.\" <ref>McLean, Craig. \"Donna Summer: Too Hot to Handle.\" The Telegraph, Telegraph Media Group, 13 June 2008.</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n*Donna Summer &ndash; lead vocals\n*Pete Bellotte &ndash; guitars\n*Dave King &ndash; bass\n*Michael Thatcher &ndash; keyboards\n*Giorgio Moroder &ndash; keyboards\n*Martin Harrison &ndash; drums\n*Lucy, Betsy, Gitta &ndash; backing vocals\n\n==Track listing and formats==\n'''Original Netherlands 7\" (Groovy GR 1211)'''\n# \"Love to Love You\" (3:20)\n# \"Need-a-Man Blues\" (?)\nNB This original release (without the \"Baby\" in the title) ran for just over 3 minutes and 20 seconds. This version was integrated into the 16-minute version found on the album. All subsequent international releases either contained a new edit of the full album version (lasting just under five minutes) or the original version (but still adding \"Baby\" to the title). In some cases (for example, the United States), both versions were found on different sides of the record.\n\n'''US 7\" (Oasis OC 401)'''\n# \"Love to Love You Baby\" (4:57)\n# \"Love to Love You Baby\" (3:27)\n\n'''UK 7\" (GTO GT 17)'''\n# \"Love to Love You Baby\" (4:57)\n# \"Need-a-Man Blues\" (?)\n\n'''Germany 7\" (Atlantic ATL 10625)'''\n# \"Love to Love You\" (3:20)\n# \"Need-a-Man Blues\" (3:09)\nNB The word \"Baby\" appears on the sleeve but not the label\n\n'''Netherlands 7\" (Groovy GR 1218)'''\n# \"Love to Love You Baby Part I\" (3:30)\n# \"Love to Love You Baby Part II\" (5:20)\nNB This Dutch re-release was issued shortly after the song became a hit internationally, with \"Baby\" being added to the title\n\n'''France 7\" (Atlantic 10.693)'''\n# \"Love to Love You Baby (Part 1)\" (3:27)\n# \"Love to Love You Baby\" (Part 2)\" (4:57)\n\n'''Canada 7\" (Oasis OC 401X)'''\n# \"Love to Love You Baby\" (3:22)\n# \"Need-a-Man Blues\" (3:12)\n\n'''Sweden 7\" (Polar POS 1209)'''\n# \"Love to Love You Baby\" (3:21)\n# \"Need-a-Man Blues\" (3:10)\n\n'''Spain 7\" (Ariola 16575)'''\n# \"Love to Love You Baby\" (3:42)\n# \"Need-a-Man Blues\" (4:30)\n\n===1983 re-issue===\nFollowing the dance chart success of the Patrick Cowley remix of Summer's \"I Feel Love\" in 1982, Casablanca Records/[[PolyGram]] re-issued her first hit single \"Love to Love You Baby\". However, the single failed to make an impact on the charts the second time around, and it would be the label's final single re-release of tracks from the Donna Summer back catalog in the 1980s. In 1984, Casablanca Records was closed by PolyGram.\n\n'''UK 7\" (Casablanca CAN 1014)'''\n# \"Love to Love You Baby\" (Part One) \u2013 3:35\n# \"Love to Love You Baby\" (Part Two) \u2013 4:12\n\n'''UK 12\" (Casablanca CANX 1014)'''\n# \"Love to Love You Baby\" (Come On Over to My Place Version) \u2013 16:50\n# \"Love to Love You Baby\" (Come Dancing Version) \u2013 8:10 <small>(A Young and Strong mega-edit)</small>\nNB: The \"Come On Over to My Place Version\" is in fact the original full-length album version\n\n===1990 re-release===\n'''Germany CD single (Casablanca 874 395-2)'''\n# \"Love to Love You Baby\" \u2013 4:15\n# \"I Feel Love\" \u2013 5:39\n# \"Bad Girls\" \u2013 3:54\n# \"On the Radio\" (long version) \u2013 5:51\n\n===2013 release===\n# \"Love to Love You Baby\" (Giorgio Moroder Remix) (featuring [[Chris Cox (DJ)|Chris Cox]]) (4:15)\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1975\u201376)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>[http://www.austchartbook.com.au/ David Kent's \"Australian Chart Book 1970-1992\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305064644/http://www.austchartbook.com.au/ |date=2016-03-05 }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|9|artist=Donna Summer|song=Love To Love You Baby}}\n|-\n|Canada Top Singles (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'')<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.4089a&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=u9874ano8k0c5b6bkp4r8qrbp3 |title= Love to love you baby in Canadian Top Singles Chart |publisher= Library and Archives Canada |accessdate= 12 June 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160927004808/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.4089a&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=u9874ano8k0c5b6bkp4r8qrbp3 |archive-date= 27 September 2016 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infodisc.fr/Bilan_S.php |title=Love to love you baby in French Chart |author=Hung Medien |accessdate=12 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050319102619/http://www.infodisc.fr/Bilan_S.php |archivedate=19 March 2005 }} You have to use the index at the top of the page and search \"Donna Summer\"</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|17\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany|6|artist=Donna Summer|song=Love To Love You Baby}}\n|-\n|Italy ([[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana|FIMI]])<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.hitparadeitalia.it/schede/l/love_to_love_you_baby.htm |title= Love to love you baby in Italian Chart |publisher= HitParadeItalia (it) |accessdate= 10 July 2013}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|11\n|-\n|Ireland ([[Irish Singles Chart|IRMA]])<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement |title= Love to love you baby in Irish Chart |publisher= IRMA |accessdate= 10 July 2013}} Only one result when searching \"Love to love you baby\"</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|11\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|17|artist=Donna Summer|song=Love To Love You Baby}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|13|artist=Donna Summer|song=Love To Love You Baby}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|8|artist=Donna Summer|song=Love To Love You Baby}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Norway|2|artist=Donna Summer|song=Love To Love You