8/http://australian-charts.com/forum.asp?todo=viewthread&id=40275 |date=2014-10-06 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|50\n|-\n|Canada (Canadian Hot 100)<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?file_num=nlc008388.5173b&brws_s=&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=u9874ano8k0c5b6bkp4r8qrbp3 |title= Top Singles \u2013 Volume 26, No. 14 & 15, January 08 1977 |work= [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] |publisher= [[Library and Archives Canada]] |accessdate= March 13, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160610094136/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?file_num=nlc008388.5173b&brws_s=&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=u9874ano8k0c5b6bkp4r8qrbp3 |archive-date= June 10, 2016 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|25\n|-\n|UK Singles (Official Charts Company)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.old-charts.com/charts70/yearend70/1976yearend_uk.htm |title=Old-Charts |publisher=Old-Charts |date= |accessdate=2015-11-12}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|61\n|-\n|US Billboard Hot 100<ref>[http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1976.htm Musicoutfitters.com]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|41\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Certifications and sales==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Canada|title=Love to Love You Baby|artist=Donna Summer|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=1975|certyear=1977}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|title=Love to Love You Baby|artist=Donna Summer|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=1975|certyear=1976|refname=US Plat}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==Cover versions and samples==\n\n*The refrain \"Love to love you\" can be heard predominantly in the background of [[Diana Ross]]' 1976 hit \"[[Love Hangover]]\". \n*In [[1982]], Indian singer [[Sharon Prabhakar]] recorded a cover of the song in Hindi, entitled \"Aaj Ki Raat\" on her album \"Disco Mastana\", released on [[Multitone]] records.\n*An excerpt of the song was featured during the first episode of ''[[The Brady Bunch Hour|The Brady Bunch Variety Hour]]'' and a subsequent tell-all book about the show was titled \"[[Love to Love You Bradys]].\"<ref name=fakejan>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Love-You-Bradys-Bizarre-Variety/dp/1550228889/|title=amazon.com: Love to Love You Bradys: The Bizarre Story of the Brady Bunch Variety Hour|accessdate=June 6, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Digital Underground]] made the song the central sample of the song \"Freaks of the Industry\" on their 1990 debut album ''[[Sex Packets]]''.\n*[[Samantha Fox]] covered her tune into a medley with ''[[More, More, More]]'' from her 1991 album ''[[Just One Night (Samantha Fox album)|Just One Night]]''.\n*[[TLC (group)|TLC]] sampled the song on the album version of their 1999 song \"[[I'm Good At Being Bad]]\".\n*[[The Tom Tom Club]] recorded a cover for their 2000 album \"[[The Good, The Bad, and the Funky]].\"<ref>https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-good-the-bad-and-the-funky-mw0000088205</ref>\n*[[Beyonc\u00e9]] also sampled the refrain of the song for her hit \"[[Naughty Girl (Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles song)|Naughty Girl]]\" on her album ''[[Dangerously in Love]]'', which she performed live for the Fashion Rocks Awards 2004 <ref>[http://www.wat.tv/video/beyonce-naugthy-girl-live-1gm8x_2i4l5_.html Seen on April 4, 2013] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102231412/http://www.wat.tv/video/beyonce-naugthy-girl-live-1gm8x_2i4l5_.html |date=January 2, 2014 }}</ref>\n*French male model and singer [[Baptiste Giabiconi]] covered it as an adaptation and heavy sampling of the hit in 2016, but with added lyrics and new EDM arrangement. His version credited to mononym Giabiconi entered the French [[SNEP]] chart at #14 in July 2016.<ref>[http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Baptiste+Giabiconi&titel=Love+To+Love+You+Baby&cat=s LesCharts.com: Baptiste Giabiconi - \"Love To Love You Baby\" song page]</ref>\n* In 2018, the song was included in the Broadway musical ''[[Summer: The Donna Summer Musical]]''.\n\n==See also==\n*[[1975 in music]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|donna-summer|love-to-love-you-baby}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Donna Summer discography}}\n{{Jimmy Somerville}}\n{{No Doubt singles}}\n{{Tom Tom Club}}\n[[Category:1975 singles]]\n[[Category:1976 singles]]\n[[Category:1983 singles]]\n[[Category:Funk ballads]]\n[[Category:Donna Summer songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Dance Club Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:RPM Top Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Pete Bellotte]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Giorgio Moroder]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Donna Summer]]\n[[Category:Samantha Fox songs]]\n[[Category:Casablanca Records singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Pete Bellotte]]\n[[Category:1975 songs]]\n[[Category:GTO Records singles]]\n[[Category:Polar Music singles]]\n[[Category:Ariola Records singles]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records singles]]\n[[Category:1970s ballads]]\n[[Category:Songs banned by the BBC]]\n[[Category:Songs about sexuality]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: on June 1975 \u2192 in June 1975 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Love_to_Love_You_Baby_(song)"}
{"title_page": "United States at the Olympics", "text_new": "{{infobox country at games\n| NOC = USA\n| NOCname = [[United States Olympic & Paralympic Committee]]\n| games = Olympics\n| year = \n| flagcaption = [[Flag of the United States]]\n| oldcode = \n| website = \n| location = \n| competitors = \n| sports = \n| flagbearer = \n| rank = 1\n| gold = 1127\n| silver = 907\n| bronze = 793\n| officials = \n| appearances = \n| app_begin_year = \n| app_end_year = \n| summerappearances = {{Team appearances list|team=United States|competition=Summer Olympics|begin_year=|end_year= }}\n| winterappearances = {{Team appearances list|team=United States|competition=Winter Olympics|begin_year=|end_year= }}\n| seealso = [[United States at the 1906 Intercalated Games|1906]] Intercalated Games\n}}\n{{See also|United States at the Summer Olympics|United States at the Winter Olympics}}\nThe '''[[United States|United States of America]]''' (USA) has sent athletes to every celebration of the modern [[Olympic Games]] with the exception of the [[1980 Summer Olympics]], during which it led a [[1980 Summer Olympics boycott|boycott]]. The [[United States Olympic & Paralympic Committee]] (USOPC) is the [[National Olympic Committee]] for the United States.\n\nFrom 1896 to 2018, U.S. athletes have won a total of 2,522 medals (1,022 of them gold) at the [[Summer Olympic Games]], more than any other nation, and another 305 at the [[Winter Olympic Games]], the second most behind [[Norway at the Olympics|Norway]]. \n\nThe United States Olympic team remains the only in the world to receive no government funding.<ref>https://www.teamusa.org/about-the-usoc</ref>\n\n== Hosted Games ==\nThe United States has hosted the Games on '''eight''' occasions, more than any other nation, and is planning to host the '''ninth''':\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Games !! Host city !! Dates !! Nations !! Participants !! Events \n|-\n|[[1904 Summer Olympics]] || [[St. Louis]], [[Missouri]] || July 1\u2013November 23 |